{"title_page": "Sikandar Hayat Khan (Azad Kashmir politician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use Pakistani English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Other uses|Sikandar Hayat Khan (disambiguation){{!}}Sikandar Hayat Khan}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox Prime Minister\n| name        = Sardar Sikandar Hayat Khan\n| image       = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1934|06|01}}\n| birth_place = [[Poonch (town)|Poonch]], [[Jammu and Kashmir]]\n| office =[[Prime Minister of Azad Jammu and Kashmir]]\n| term_start =17 June 1985\n| term_end =28 June 1990\n| predecessor = Abdul Hamid Khan\n| successor = [[Raja Mummtaz Hussain Rathore]]\n| term_start2 =25 July 2001\n| term_end2 =23 July 2006\n| predecessor2 = [[Barrister Sultan Mahmood]]\n| successor2 =[[Sardar Attique Ahmed Khan]]\n| office3 = [[President of Azad Jammu and Kashmir]]\n| term_start3 = 12 August 1991\n| term_end3 = 11 May 1996\n| predecessor3 = [[Abdul Rasheed Abbasi]] (Speaker Assembly / Acting)\n| successor3 = [[Abdul Rasheed Abbasi]] (Speaker Assembly / Acting)\n| term_start4 = 23 May 1996\n| term_end4 = 11 August 1996\n| predecessor4 = [[Abdul Rasheed Abbasi]] (Speaker Assembly / Acting)\n| successor4 = [[Raja Mummtaz Hussain Rathore]](Speaker Assembly / Acting)\n}}\n'''Sardar Sikandar Hayat Khan''' ({{lang-ur|\u0633\u0631\u062f\u0627\u0631 \u0633\u0650\u06a9\u0646\u062f\u0631 \u062d\u06cc\u0627\u062a \u062e\u0627\u0646}}) (born 1 June 1934) was twice a former Prime Minister and President of [[Azad Kashmir|Azad Jammu and Kashmir]]. He has been the longest serving Prime Minister of Azad Jammu and Kashmir.\n\nSardar Sikandar Hayat Khan was born into an eminent political family of Kashmir, he is the son of Sardar Fateh Muhammad Khan Karelvi, a name synonymous with one of the first major uprisings against the  [[Dogra]] regime in 1931. It was Sardar Fateh Muhammad Khan Karelvi, who led the popular agitation against an arbitrary tax on salt imposed by the Maharaja's regime. \n\n==Education==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2012}}\nGrowing up, Sardar Sikandar Hayat Khan received his early schooling in his native village of Karela in tehsil [[Fatehpur Thakiala]], now in District Kotli and in [[Poonch (town)|Poonch]] city. Sardar Sikandar Hayat Khan came to the famous [[Gordon College (Rawalpindi)]] from where he graduated in 1956 before going on to the University Law College in Lahore to obtain a law degree in 1958.\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2012}}\nHe returned to [[Kotli]] to start a law practice and also formally joined the [[All Jammu and Kashmir Muslim Conference]], an association he has maintained with consistency and has come to be recognized as the hallmark of his politics. He also successfully ran for membership of the local council, a position he occupied for eight years and during this period was also elected as President of Bar Association, Kotli. In 1970, he was elected to the Azad Jammu & Kashmir Legislative Assembly.\n\nHe has been returned to office from his constituency in every election held in Azad Kashmir between 1970 and 2001, barring the years when he was President of Azad Kashmir. His brother Sardar Muhammad Naeem Khan<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pmajk.gov.pk/CV_naeem_khan.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-07-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209165427/http://www.pmajk.gov.pk/CV_naeem_khan.asp |archivedate=2012-02-09 }}</ref> served as a member from that area during that period.\n\nSardar Sikandar Hayat Khan was inducted into the Azad Jammu & Kashmir cabinet as Minister of Revenue, Forests and Finance in 1972 and retained that portfolio for the next three years. He served as acting President of the Jammu & Kashmir Muslim Conference in the 1976\u201378 period and was elected President in 1978, a position he held until 1988.\n\nIn 1985, he was elected Prime Minister of Azad Jammu & Kashmir and retained that office for the next five years. He remained leader of the opposition in the Assembly during the next two years, before he was elected President of Azad Jammu & Kashmir for a five-year term in 1991.\n\nHe was sworn in as Prime Minister of Azad Jammu & Kashmir on 25 July 2001 for the second time and retired from active politics in July 2006 after completing his second term. But later he played a major role in introducing PML-(N) in Azad Jammu and Kashmir which was acknowledged by giving him a position of Senior Vice President of [[Pakistan Muslim League (N)]] in 2011.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=Sardar Mohammad Abdul Qayyum Khan }} \n{{s-ttl|title= [[President of Azad Jammu and Kashmir]] |years=1991\u20131996 }}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sardar Muhammad Ibrahim Khan]] }}\n{{s-bef|before=Abdul Hamid Khan}}\n{{s-ttl|title= [[Prime Minister of Azad Jammu and Kashmir]] |years=1985-1990}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Raja Mummtaz Hussain Rathore]]}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Barrister Sultan Mahmood]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= [[Prime Minister of Azad Jammu and Kashmir]] |years=2001-2006}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Sardar Attique Ahmed Khan]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130715035603/http://www.pmajk.gov.pk/former%20PMs.asp Prime Ministers of Azad Jammu and Kashmir]\n* [http://www.ajk.gov.pk/site/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2875&Itemid=114 Presidents of Azad Jammu and Kashmir]\n* [http://www.ajk.gov.pk Government of Azad Kashmir]\n\n{{Presidents of Azad Kashmir}}\n{{Prime Ministers of Azad Kashmir}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan, Sikandar Hayat}}\n[[Category:People from Poonch District, Pakistan]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Azad Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Government Gordon College alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use Pakistani English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Other uses|Sikandar Hayat Khan (disambiguation){{!}}Sikandar Hayat Khan}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox Prime Minister\n| name        = Sardar Sikandar Hayat Khan\n| image       = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1934|06|01}}\n| birth_place = [[Poonch (town)|Poonch]], [[Jammu and Kashmir]]\n| office =[[Prime Minister of Azad Jammu and Kashmir]]\n| term_start =17 June 1985\n| term_end =28 June 1990\n| predecessor = Abdul Hamid Khan\n| successor = [[Raja Mummtaz Hussain Rathore]]\n| term_start2 =25 July 2001\n| term_end2 =23 July 2006\n| predecessor2 = [[Barrister Sultan Mahmood]]\n| successor2 =[[Sardar Attique Ahmed Khan]]\n| office3 = [[President of Azad Jammu and Kashmir]]\n| term_start3 = 12 August 1991\n| term_end3 = 11 May 1996\n| predecessor3 = [[Abdul Rasheed Abbasi]] (Speaker Assembly / Acting)\n| successor3 = [[Abdul Rasheed Abbasi]] (Speaker Assembly / Acting)\n| term_start4 = 23 May 1996\n| term_end4 = 11 August 1996\n| predecessor4 = [[Abdul Rasheed Abbasi]] (Speaker Assembly / Acting)\n| successor4 = [[Raja Mummtaz Hussain Rathore]](Speaker Assembly / Acting)\n}}\n'''Sardar Sikandar Hayat Khan''' ({{lang-ur|\u0633\u0631\u062f\u0627\u0631 \u0633\u0650\u06a9\u0646\u062f\u0631 \u062d\u06cc\u0627\u062a \u062e\u0627\u0646}}) (born 1 June 1934) was twice a former Prime Minister and President of [[Azad Kashmir|Azad Jammu and Kashmir]]. He has been the longest serving Prime Minister of Azad Jammu and Kashmir.\n\nSardar Sikandar Hayat Khan was born into an eminent political family of Kashmir, he is the son of [[Sardar Fateh Muhammad Khan Karelvi]], a name synonymous with one of the first major uprisings against the  [[Dogra]] regime in 1931. It was [[Sardar Fateh Muhammad Khan Karelvi]], who led the popular agitation against an arbitrary tax on salt imposed by the Maharaja's regime. \n\n==Education==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2012}}\nGrowing up, Sardar Sikandar Hayat Khan received his early schooling in his native village of Karela in tehsil [[Fatehpur Thakiala]], now in District Kotli and in [[Poonch (town)|Poonch]] city. Sardar Sikandar Hayat Khan came to the famous [[Gordon College (Rawalpindi)]] from where he graduated in 1956 before going on to the University Law College in Lahore to obtain a law degree in 1958.\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2012}}\nHe returned to [[Kotli]] to start a law practice and also formally joined the [[All Jammu and Kashmir Muslim Conference]], an association he has maintained with consistency and has come to be recognized as the hallmark of his politics. He also successfully ran for membership of the local council, a position he occupied for eight years and during this period was also elected as President of Bar Association, Kotli. In 1970, he was elected to the Azad Jammu & Kashmir Legislative Assembly.\n\nHe has been returned to office from his constituency in every election held in Azad Kashmir between 1970 and 2001, barring the years when he was President of Azad Kashmir. His brother Sardar Muhammad Naeem Khan<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pmajk.gov.pk/CV_naeem_khan.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-07-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209165427/http://www.pmajk.gov.pk/CV_naeem_khan.asp |archivedate=2012-02-09 }}</ref> served as a member from that area during that period.\n\nSardar Sikandar Hayat Khan was inducted into the Azad Jammu & Kashmir cabinet as Minister of Revenue, Forests and Finance in 1972 and retained that portfolio for the next three years. He served as acting President of the Jammu & Kashmir Muslim Conference in the 1976\u201378 period and was elected President in 1978, a position he held until 1988.\n\nIn 1985, he was elected Prime Minister of Azad Jammu & Kashmir and retained that office for the next five years. He remained leader of the opposition in the Assembly during the next two years, before he was elected President of Azad Jammu & Kashmir for a five-year term in 1991.\n\nHe was sworn in as Prime Minister of Azad Jammu & Kashmir on 25 July 2001 for the second time and retired from active politics in July 2006 after completing his second term. But later he played a major role in introducing PML-(N) in Azad Jammu and Kashmir which was acknowledged by giving him a position of Senior Vice President of [[Pakistan Muslim League (N)]] in 2011.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=Sardar Mohammad Abdul Qayyum Khan }} \n{{s-ttl|title= [[President of Azad Jammu and Kashmir]] |years=1991\u20131996 }}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sardar Muhammad Ibrahim Khan]] }}\n{{s-bef|before=Abdul Hamid Khan}}\n{{s-ttl|title= [[Prime Minister of Azad Jammu and Kashmir]] |years=1985-1990}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Raja Mummtaz Hussain Rathore]]}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Barrister Sultan Mahmood]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= [[Prime Minister of Azad Jammu and Kashmir]] |years=2001-2006}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Sardar Attique Ahmed Khan]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130715035603/http://www.pmajk.gov.pk/former%20PMs.asp Prime Ministers of Azad Jammu and Kashmir]\n* [http://www.ajk.gov.pk/site/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2875&Itemid=114 Presidents of Azad Jammu and Kashmir]\n* [http://www.ajk.gov.pk Government of Azad Kashmir]\n\n{{Presidents of Azad Kashmir}}\n{{Prime Ministers of Azad Kashmir}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan, Sikandar Hayat}}\n[[Category:People from Poonch District, Pakistan]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Azad Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Government Gordon College alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Fateh Muhammad Khan Karelviclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sikandar_Hayat_Khan_(Azad_Kashmir_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Fatehpur Thakiala", "text_new": "{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n'''Fatehpur Thakiala''', also known as '''Nakyal''', is one of the three ''[[tehsil]]s'' of the [[Kotli District]] in [[Azad Kashmir]], [[Pakistan]].\n\n==History==\nFatehpur Thakiala was part of the Mendhar subdivision of [[Historical Poonch District|Poonch]] before the partition of [[Kashmir]] in 1947. Fatehpur Thakiala is bounded by the Line of Control\u2014the boundary between Indian and [[Pakistan administered Kashmir]]\u2014on its north and east sides. The 1947\u201348 war between India and Pakistan divided it into two parts; one part went to Pakistan and the other became part of India. After the separation from [[Mendhar]], it became a ''tehsil'' of the [[Kotli District]].\n\nThe original name of the area was Thakiala, named after the native Thakial Rajputs.  It was renamed Fatehpur Thakiala to honour the late Sardar Fateh Muhammad Khan Karelvi.  It is also the birthplace of the former president and prime minister of Azad Kashmir, [[Sardar Sikandar Hayat Khan]].\n\n==Location==\nThe town of Nakyal is 1524&nbsp;m above sea level, and is 40&nbsp;km from [[Kotli]] city.\n\nNakyal is in a valley nearly 3 kilometres from the Line of Control. Nearby Tatapani is one of the five crossing points at the Line of Control that were opened for the exchange of relief goods between Pakistani and Indian Administered parts of Kashmir after the devastating October 8{{when|date=December 2012}} earthquake.\n\n==Demographics==\nThe Gujjar are one of the major ethnic groups in Fatehpur.  The Gujjar clans are the Kallas, Bagri, Bajar, Bhumbla, Bjarh, Chandpuri, Chauhan, Chechi, Hans, Khatana, Laley, Khepar, Meelu, and Sangoo. The Rajput are second most numerous of the major ethnic groups.  The subclans of Rajputs are the Thakyals, Ghakhars, and Dhumals. The Kashmiri tribe's main clans in Nakyal include the Butt and Lone.  They are the descendants of Kashmiri workmen who migrated to the plains of Punjab from the Kashmir Valley in the 16th and 17th centuries.  The fourth major tribe is the Malik.\n\n{{Kotli District}}\n{{Tehsils of Azad Kashmir}}\n[[Category:Kotli District]]\n[[Category:Tehsils of Kotli District]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n'''Fatehpur Thakiala''', also known as '''Nakyal''', is one of the three ''[[tehsil]]s'' of the [[Kotli District]] in [[Azad Kashmir]], [[Pakistan]].\n\n==History==\nFatehpur Thakiala was part of the Mendhar subdivision of [[Historical Poonch District|Poonch]] before the partition of [[Kashmir]] in 1947. Fatehpur Thakiala is bounded by the Line of Control\u2014the boundary between Indian and [[Pakistan administered Kashmir]]\u2014on its north and east sides. The 1947\u201348 war between India and Pakistan divided it into two parts; one part went to Pakistan and the other became part of India. After the separation from [[Mendhar]], it became a ''tehsil'' of the [[Kotli District]].\n\nThe original name of the area was Thakiala, named after the native Thakial Rajputs.  It was renamed Fatehpur Thakiala to honour the late [[Sardar Fateh Muhammad Khan Karelvi]].  It is also the birthplace of the former president and prime minister of Azad Kashmir, [[Sardar Sikandar Hayat Khan]].\n\n==Location==\nThe town of Nakyal is 1524&nbsp;m above sea level, and is 40&nbsp;km from [[Kotli]] city.\n\nNakyal is in a valley nearly 3 kilometres from the Line of Control. Nearby Tatapani is one of the five crossing points at the Line of Control that were opened for the exchange of relief goods between Pakistani and Indian Administered parts of Kashmir after the devastating October 8{{when|date=December 2012}} earthquake.\n\n==Demographics==\nThe Gujjar are one of the major ethnic groups in Fatehpur.  The Gujjar clans are the Kallas, Bagri, Bajar, Bhumbla, Bjarh, Chandpuri, Chauhan, Chechi, Hans, Khatana, Laley, Khepar, Meelu, and Sangoo. The Rajput are second most numerous of the major ethnic groups.  The subclans of Rajputs are the Thakyals, Ghakhars, and Dhumals. The Kashmiri tribe's main clans in Nakyal include the Butt and Lone.  They are the descendants of Kashmiri workmen who migrated to the plains of Punjab from the Kashmir Valley in the 16th and 17th centuries.  The fourth major tribe is the Malik.\n\n{{Kotli District}}\n{{Tehsils of Azad Kashmir}}\n[[Category:Kotli District]]\n[[Category:Tehsils of Kotli District]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Fateh Muhammad Khan Karelviclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fatehpur_Thakiala"}
{"title_page": "Ghilad", "text_new": "{{distinguish|text=[[Ghil'ad (disambiguation)|Ghil'ad]] or [[Gilad (disambiguation)|Gilad]] or [[Gilead (disambiguation)|Gilead]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Timi\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Timi\u0219 County\n|name=Ghilad\n|leader_name= Cornel Guran\n|leader_party= PNL\n|image_map              = Ghilad jud Timis.png\n|coordinates = {{coord|45|28|N|21|9|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Ghilad''' ({{lang-de|Gilad}} or ''Kilatt''; {{lang-hu|Gil\u00e1d}}) is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] in [[Timi\u0219 County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of two villages, Gad (''G\u00e1d'') and Ghilad. These were part of [[Ciacova]] Commune until 2004, when they were split off.\n\n==History==\nAccording to [https://web.archive.org/web/20170111021029/http://ghilad-belacrkva.eu/en/ghilad-commune/]:\n\n* 10th century \u2013 According to a legend, there was a battle between the Romanian Voivode [[Glad (duke)|(duke) Glad]] and the Hungarian army in the place of the present-day village of Gad. Glad might be the origin of Ghilad.\n* 12th century \u2013 the locality of Ghilad was named Gyad and then Galad.\n* 1212 - the commune was given to a count named Sebus by King Andrew II of Hungary.\n* 16th century \u2013 the beglerbeg Rami of Timi\u0219oara brought several Romanian families from Transylvania to Ghilad.\n* 17th century \u2013 the village of Gad was plundered by the Ottomans.\n* 1717 \u2013 present: Ghilad was mentioned under the name of Gor ni Gilad (with 80 houses) and Dolni Gilad (with 100 houses); the settlement of Gad had 30 houses.\n* 1721 - several German families settled in the area.\n* 1842 - several Hungarian families settled in the area.\n* 1851-1860 \u2013 Hungarian and German families settled in the area.\n* 1900 \u2013 35% of the inhabitants of the village of Gad were Serbian.\n* 1926 \u2013 Ghilad had 3,589 inhabitants.\n* 1936 \u2013 Ghilad had three churches, a primary school, a cultural centre, a historical monument, a military band, two town libraries, a men\u2019s choir, 850 houses, 3,539 inhabitants. Gad had a Serbian and German state school, a men\u2019s choir, a mixed choir, a sports club, a monument dedicated to heroes.\n* 20 February 1942 \u2013 Ioan (Ionel) Bogdan was born in Gad, instrumental performer and conductor.\n* 1947 \u2013 Viorel Cristea was born in Ghilad, well-known naive painter (d. 15 May 1993).\n* 2002 \u2013 Ghilad and Gad had 1,849 inhabitants.\n* 2004 \u2013 the commune of Ghilad was re-founded by separating from the town of Ciacova.\n* 2009 \u2013 12 kilometres of road between Ghilad and Gad (the latter with 185 inhabitants) were paved with stone.\n\n{{Timi\u0219 County}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Timi\u0219 County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Romanian Banat]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|text=[[Ghil'ad (disambiguation)|Ghil'ad]] or [[Gilad (disambiguation)|Gilad]] or [[Gilead (disambiguation)|Gilead]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Timi\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Timi\u0219 County\n|name=Ghilad\n|leader_name= Cornel Guran\n|leader_party= [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|PNL]]\n|image_map=\n|coordinates = {{coord|45|28|N|21|9|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Ghilad''' ({{lang-de|Gilad}} or ''Kilatt''; {{lang-hu|Gil\u00e1d}}) is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] in [[Timi\u0219 County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of two villages, Gad (''G\u00e1d'') and Ghilad. These were part of [[Ciacova]] Commune until 2004, when they were split off.\n\n==History==\nAccording to [https://web.archive.org/web/20170111021029/http://ghilad-belacrkva.eu/en/ghilad-commune/]:\n\n* 10th century \u2013 According to a legend, there was a battle between the Romanian Voivode [[Glad (duke)|(duke) Glad]] and the Hungarian army in the place of the present-day village of Gad. Glad might be the origin of Ghilad.\n* 12th century \u2013 the locality of Ghilad was named Gyad and then Galad.\n* 1212 - the commune was given to a count named Sebus by King Andrew II of Hungary.\n* 16th century \u2013 the beglerbeg Rami of Timi\u0219oara brought several Romanian families from Transylvania to Ghilad.\n* 17th century \u2013 the village of Gad was plundered by the Ottomans.\n* 1717 \u2013 present: Ghilad was mentioned under the name of Gor ni Gilad (with 80 houses) and Dolni Gilad (with 100 houses); the settlement of Gad had 30 houses.\n* 1721 - several German families settled in the area.\n* 1842 - several Hungarian families settled in the area.\n* 1851-1860 \u2013 Hungarian and German families settled in the area.\n* 1900 \u2013 35% of the inhabitants of the village of Gad were Serbian.\n* 1926 \u2013 Ghilad had 3,589 inhabitants.\n* 1936 \u2013 Ghilad had three churches, a primary school, a cultural centre, a historical monument, a military band, two town libraries, a men\u2019s choir, 850 houses, 3,539 inhabitants. Gad had a Serbian and German state school, a men\u2019s choir, a mixed choir, a sports club, a monument dedicated to heroes.\n* 20 February 1942 \u2013 Ioan (Ionel) Bogdan was born in Gad, instrumental performer and conductor.\n* 1947 \u2013 Viorel Cristea was born in Ghilad, well-known naive painter (d. 15 May 1993).\n* 2002 \u2013 Ghilad and Gad had 1,849 inhabitants.\n* 2004 \u2013 the commune of Ghilad was re-founded by separating from the town of Ciacova.\n* 2009 \u2013 12 kilometres of road between Ghilad and Gad (the latter with 185 inhabitants) were paved with stone.\n\n{{Timi\u0219 County}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Timi\u0219 County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Romanian Banat]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghilad"}
{"title_page": "Asja Paladin", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Asja Paladin\n| image          = Asja Paladin, Giro Rosa 2016.jpg\n| caption        = Paladin during the [[2016 Giro d'Italia Femminile]]\n| fullname       = Asja Paladin\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1994|9|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    =\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    = {{ct|VAL}}\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| amateurteam1   =\n| proyears1      = 2013\u20132017\n| proteam1       = {{ct|TOP|2013}}\n| proyears2      = 2018\u2013\n| proteam2       = {{ct|VAL|2018}}\n| majorwins      =\n| medaltemplates =\n| show-medals    =\n}}\n'''Asja Paladin''' (born 27 September 1994) is an Italian professional [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]], who currently rides for [[UCI Women's Team]] {{ct|VAL}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/cylance-signs-on-with-italian-team-valcar-for-2019/|title=Cylance signs on with Italian team Valcar for 2019|first=Pat|last=Malach|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|date=8 January 2019|accessdate=10 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Major results==\n;2018\n:1st [[File:Jersey polkadot.svg|20px]] Mountains classification [[2018 Emakumeen Euskal Bira|Emakumeen Euskal Bira]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Top Girls Fassa Bortolo]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|70836}}\n*{{ProCyclingStats|168659}}\n\n{{Valcar\u2013Cylance riders}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paladin, Asja}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian female cyclists]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1990s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Asja Paladin\n| image          = Asja Paladin, Giro Rosa 2016.jpg\n| caption        = Paladin during the [[2016 Giro d'Italia Femminile]]\n| fullname       = Asja Paladin\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1994|9|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    =\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    = {{ct|VAL}}\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| amateurteam1   =\n| proyears1      = 2013\u20132017\n| proteam1       = {{ct|TOP|2013}}\n| proyears2      = 2018\u2013\n| proteam2       = {{ct|VAL|2018}}\n| majorwins      =\n| medaltemplates =\n| show-medals    =\n}}\n'''Asja Paladin''' (born 27 September 1994) is an Italian professional [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]], who currently rides for [[UCI Women's Team]] {{ct|VAL}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/cylance-signs-on-with-italian-team-valcar-for-2019/|title=Cylance signs on with Italian team Valcar for 2019|first=Pat|last=Malach|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|date=8 January 2019|accessdate=10 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Major results==\n;2018\n:1st [[File:Jersey polkadot.svg|20px]] Mountains classification [[2018 Emakumeen Euskal Bira|Emakumeen Euskal Bira]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Top Girls Fassa Bortolo]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|70836}}\n*{{ProCyclingStats|168659}}\n\n{{Valcar\u2013Cylance riders}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paladin, Asja}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian female cyclists]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1990s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asja_Paladin"}
{"title_page": "Mizter Okyere", "text_new": "'''Daniel Okyere Donkor''' popularly known with his stage name '''Mizter Okyere''' is a Ghanaian [[saxophonist]] and [[Record producer|producer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/entertainment/2019/July-26th/joy-fm-cosmopolitan-mix-mixter-okyere-band-performs-live.php|title=Joy FM Cosmopolitan Mix - Mixter Okyere, band performs live|website=www.myjoyonline.com|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/3G-Awards-2019-Mizter-Okyere-to-be-honoured-in-New-York-781091|title=3G Awards 2019 - Mizter Okyere to be honoured in New York|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> In 2019, he was awarded the Best Instrumentalist of the Year at the [[Vodafone Ghana Music Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Mizter-Okyere-crowned-Instrumentalist-of-the-Year-at-VGMA-2019-748934|title=Mizter Okyere crowned Instrumentalist of the Year at VGMA 2019|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and career ==\nMizter Okyere was born in [[Kumasi]] in the Ashanti Region of Ghana and the first of three children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsghana.com.gh/10-kumasi-artistes-that-ghanaian-should-watch-out-for-in-2019/|title=10 Kumasi Artistes That Ghanaian Should Watch Out for in 2019|last=Dzokpo|first=Ike|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> He completed St. Mary's Anglican JHS and [[KNUST Senior High School]] for his second cycle education. Upon completion, he furthered his education at [[NIIT]] where he studied Networking and Computer Programming.\n\n== Career ==\nMizter Okyere who was formally called Bigdee started his music career from church as an instrumentalist and through that established his own recording studio Bigdee Beat Studio currently called Mizter Okyere Music Studio.\n\n== Notable performances ==\nMizter Okyere has performed on stages like Rhythms on the Runway, Takoradi Music Awards, African Legends Night, Rapperholic,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://empirefmonline.com/2018/01/10/mizter-okyere-engages-sarkodie-in-a-spectacular-glory-performance-at-rapperholic-2017/|title=Mizter Okyere engages Sarkodie in a spectacular \u2018Glory\u2019 performance at Rapperholic 2017 {{!}} EmpireFM Online|last=empirefm|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> Vodafone Ghana Music Awards, Ghana Meets Naija, Miss Universe Ghana, Easter Comedy Show, MMC Live, Ghana Beverage Awards, Glo Mega Music Show, Bhim Concert,<ref>{{Citation|title=Mizter Okyere performed with Stonebwoy @ the Bhim Concert 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4nTC1Avo1e8|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> Saminifest,<ref>{{Citation|title=Samini And Mizter Okyere Sax Perform \u2018MY OWN\u2019 at SaminiFest 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dQfabCwRSW0&list=LLcIxM6quKHnhDfuO6Yr9oNA&index=6|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> [[Glitz Style Awards]], 3G Awards,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/3G-Awards-2019-Mizter-Okyere-to-be-honoured-in-New-York-781091|title=3G Awards 2019 - Mizter Okyere to be honoured in New York|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> Emy Awards, GUBA Awards,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://face2faceafrica.com/article/3-african-presidents-celebs-and-more-attend-guba-awards-usa-to-celebrate-ghanaian-excellence-photos|title=3 African presidents, celebs and more attend GUBA Awards USA to celebrate Ghanaian excellence [Photos]|date=2019-09-30|website=Face2Face Africa|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> [[NPP (Ghana)|NPP]] Loyal Ladies Cook Out and has also performed alongside [[Samini]] , [[Sarkodie (rapper)|Sarkodie]], [[Stonebwoy]], Becca et al.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ameyawdebrah.com/watch-mizter-okyere-presents-gospel-praise-a-sax-medley/|title=WATCH: Mizter Okyere presents 'Gospel Praise', a Sax Medley|last=Debrah|first=Ameyaw|date=2019-02-06|website=AmeyawDebrah.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\n== Award and nomination ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Award ceremony\n!Prize\n!Nominated work\n!Result\n!Ref\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Ghana Music Awards UK]]\n|Uncovered Artiste of the Year\n|Himself\n|{{Nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Ghana-Music-Awards-UK-2018-Full-list-of-nominees-669942|title=Ghana Music Awards UK 2018: Full list of nominees|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2019\n|Ghana Music & Arts Awards Europe\n|Instrumentalist of the Year\n|Himself\n|{{Won}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanamusic.com/news/top-stories/2019/11/20/winners-ghana-music-arts-awards-europe-2019/|title=Winners - Ghana Music & Arts Awards Europe 2019 {{!}} Ghana Music {{!}}|date=2019-11-20|website=Ghana Music|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n|-\n|3G Awards\n|Instrumentalist of the Year\n|Himself\n|{{Won}}\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Vodafone Ghana Music Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Instrumentalist of the Year\n|Himself\n|{{Won}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2019/05/full-list-of-all-winners-at-2019-vgma/|title=Full list of all winners at 2019 VGMA|date=2019-05-19|website=Citinewsroom - Comprehensive News in Ghana, Current Affairs,  Business News , Headlines, Ghana Sports, Entertainment, Politics, Articles, Opinions, Viral Content|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n|-\n|2020\n|Himself\n|{{Nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ghanamusicawards.com/nominees/|title=Nominees|website=VGMA 2020|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{Ghana-bio-stub}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Okyere, Mizter}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian record producers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Daniel Okyere Donkor''' popularly known with his stage name