{"title_page": "2019 Cyprus rape allegation case", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=January 2020}}\nThe '''2019 Cyprus rape allegation case''' was a high-profile case of alleged gang rape in [[Cyprus]]. In July 2019, a British woman on vacation in [[Ayia Napa]] alleged she had been gang raped by twelve Israeli tourists. The Israeli men were subsequently arrested and investigated over the allegation by the [[Cyprus Police]], but they were subsequently released without charge and the woman was detained for making a false allegation after she retracted her statement. In January 2020, the woman was convicted of \"public mischief\" in a Cypriot court and received a suspended sentence. The case triggered international concerns about the way the case had been handled by the Cypriot authorities. The woman has maintained that she was forced to retract her statement under pressure, something contested by Cypriot authorities. \n\n==Alleged crime and police investigation==\nDuring the 2019 summer break, the 19-year old British woman had traveled to Pambos Napa Rocks resort in the Cypriot resort town of [[Ayia Napa]] on a working holiday organised by the British tourism company Summer Takeaways.<ref name=\"UK tour firm Guardian\">{{cite news |last1=Halliday |first1=Josh |last2=Smith |first2=Helena |title=UK tour firm used by teenager in gang rape case ends trips to Ayia Napa |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/jan/03/uk-tour-firm-used-teenager-gang-case-ends-trips-ayia-napa |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=3 January 2020|archive-url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/jan/03/uk-tour-firm-used-teenager-gang-case-ends-trips-ayia-napa|archive-date=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Telegraph holiday firm\">{{cite news |title=UK working holiday firm ends Ayia Napa trips over rape claim |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/03/uk-working-holiday-firm-ends-ayia-napa-trips-rape-claim/ |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=3 January 2020}}</ref> On 17 July 2019, the British teenager filed a report with the Cyprus Police in Ayia Napa claiming that she had been raped by several Israeli youths in her hotel room. The following day, the Cypriot authorities arrested 12 Israeli youths, aged between 15 and 22 years, for eight days. The police investigation was led by Detective Sergeant Marios Christou. Police questioned the suspects and took DNA samples from all twelve. Police found five used condoms and thirteen condom wrappers in the room.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cypriot police question Israeli suspects in alleged gang rape |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/cypriot-police-question-israeli-suspects-in-alleged-gang-rape/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=20 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://www.timesofisrael.com/cypriot-police-question-israeli-suspects-in-alleged-gang-rape |archivedate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe woman was examined by Cypriot state pathologist Dr. Sophocles Sophocleus, who found no evidence of gang rape. He subsequently testified that he found a few light bruises on her thighs and scratches on her legs but in his opinion, they were not consistent with gang rape. He also examined the woman's vagina together with a gynecologist and reported finding no lesions or other injuries.<ref>{{cite news |title=British teenager in gang rape case had no serious physical injuries, doctor tells Cyprus court |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/29/british-teenager-gang-rape-case-had-no-serious-physical-injuries/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=29 November 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217093447/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/29/british-teenager-gang-rape-case-had-no-serious-physical-injuries/ |archivedate=17 February 2020}}</ref> However, private forensic pathologist Dr. [[Marios Matsakis]], who was hired by her family to participate in the case, reported that there was clear evidence of gang rape. Later testifying for her defense at trial, he stated he found bruising across her legs, arms, and buttocks from photographs of her injuries shown in court, claiming that he identified 35 separate bruises, and that the injuries left \"no doubt\" of gang rape.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayia Napa teen 'who made up rape' had 35 bruises that judge said were 'jellyfish stings' |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/ayia-napa-teen-who-made-21216145 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=5 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217093447/https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/ayia-napa-teen-who-made-21216145 |archivedate=17 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dillon |first1=Nancy |title=British teen convicted of lying about gang rape by Israeli men in Cyprus, vows appeal |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/ny-british-woman-plans-tappeal-verdict-she-lied-about-cyprus-gang-rape-20191230-6evewm2stbhhlbt42wujlx7vhu-story.html |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[New York Daily News]] |date=30 December 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217093447/https://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/ny-british-woman-plans-tappeal-verdict-she-lied-about-cyprus-gang-rape-20191230-6evewm2stbhhlbt42wujlx7vhu-story.html |archivedate=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>https://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/ny-british-woman-plans-tappeal-verdict-she-lied-about-cyprus-gang-rape-20191230-6evewm2stbhhlbt42wujlx7vhu-story.html</ref> He also criticized Sophocleus for allegedly improperly investigating her. \n\nOn 25 July, five of the youths were released due to a lack of DNA evidence connecting them to the alleged incident.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\" /> Seven remained detained. In addition to the allegation of gang rape, they were suspected of conspiracy to commit a crime, including those whose DNA was not found on the complainant.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Blumenthal |first1=Itay |title=Israeli teens arrested for gang-rape in Cyprus also suspected of conspiracy to commit crime |url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5555394,00.html |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[Ynet]] |publisher=[[Yedioth Ahronot]] |date=22 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217093447/https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5555394,00.html |archivedate=17 February 2020}}</ref> Following DNA testing, police linked three of the detained to the case and also found three more DNA samples not matching any of the accused. Police suspected that three Israelis had participated but had subsequently returned to Israel, and prepared to send a team to Israel to work in coordination with the [[Israel Police]] and Israeli travel agencies to identify them.<ref>{{cite news |title=After DNA tests, Cyprus police think 3 further gang rape suspects fled to Israel |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/after-dna-tests-cyprus-police-think-3-further-gang-rape-suspects-fled-to-israel/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=26 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191018164033/https://www.timesofisrael.com/after-dna-tests-cyprus-police-think-3-further-gang-rape-suspects-fled-to-israel/ |archivedate=26 July 2019}}</ref> On 27 July, it was reported that three of the suspects were set to be charged, with police likely to release at least two other suspects. There were conflicting reports over whether or not police would offer immunity from prosecution to one or two of the suspects in exchange for information on other suspects still being sought. Police said they have taken statements from 36 witnesses and that they were planning to interview 20 more.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cypriot police said set to charge at least 3 Israeli teens in gang rape case |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/cypriot-police-said-set-to-charge-at-least-3-israeli-teens-in-gang-rape-case/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=27 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209084342/https://www.timesofisrael.com/cypriot-police-said-set-to-charge-at-least-3-israeli-teens-in-gang-rape-case/ |archivedate=9 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the investigation turned toward the British woman. According to an attorney for some of the Israelis, they were able to provide convincing evidence of their innocence.<ref>{{cite news |title=All Israeli suspects in Cyprus gang rape released; British complainant arrested |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/all-israeli-suspects-in-cyprus-gang-rape-to-be-released-lawyer-says/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=28 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223174445/https://www.timesofisrael.com/all-israeli-suspects-in-cyprus-gang-rape-to-be-released-lawyer-says/ |archivedate=23 February 2020}}</ref> On 27 July, the British teenager visited a police station to give a statement but was instead accused of lying about allegations. Following eight hours of questioning without a lawyer, the woman signed a statement retracting her rape allegations:\n<blockquote>The report I did on the 17th of July 2019 that I was raped at ayia napa was not the truth. The truth is that I wasnt raped and everything that happened in that appartment was with my consent. The reason I made the statement with the fake report is because I did not know they were recording & humiliating me that night I discovered them recording me doing sexual intercourse and I felt embarrassed as I want to appologise, and say I made a mistake.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Morley |first1=Nathan |title=Linguist casts doubt on rape retraction statement |url=https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/11/15/linguist-casts-doubt-on-rape-retraction-statement/ |accessdate=16 January 2020 |work=[[Cyprus Mail]] |date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ames |first1=Jonathan |title=Cyprus rape case: Experts cast doubt on teenager\u2019s confession |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/cyprus-rape-case-experts-cast-doubt-on-teenagers-confession-x8r9s3xcc |accessdate=16 January 2020 |work=[[The Times]] |date=3 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325161923/https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/11/15/linguist-casts-doubt-on-rape-retraction-statement/|archive-date=25 March 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\nThe defence has contended that the defendant made the statement while under duress. Cypriot authorities charged her with \"giving a false statement over an imaginary offence.\" On 28 July, the remaining Israeli suspects were released from custody.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\" /> Cypriot Police claimed that the woman had got angry when her alleged attackers had filmed her having consensual sex with some of the alleged attackers and alleged she had been raped. Nir Yaslovitch, a lawyer representing several of the Israeli youths, said that his clients would seek legal damages against her for false rape allegations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elizera |first1=Rotem |title=All Israeli teens in Cyprus rape case freed as British accuser arrested |url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5558680,00.html |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[Ynet]] |date=28 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112025311/https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5558680,00.html|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hadjicostis |first1=Menelaos |title=7 Israeli Teens Freed After Woman Recants Cyprus Rape Report |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-28/lawyer-cyprus-will-free-7-israelis-detained-in-rape-case |accessdate=12 January 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |date=28 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112024609/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-28/lawyer-cyprus-will-free-7-israelis-detained-in-rape-case|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legal proceedings==\nOn 30 July, the woman appeared at the Famagusta District Court in [[Paralimni]], where she was charged with acts of \"public mischief\" and remanded into custody for eight days.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\" /> On 6 August 2019, the defendant repudiated her retraction statement, claiming that she had been coerced into producing it by the Cypriot Police. Her lawyer Andreas Pittadjis resigned due to a \"serious disagreement\" with his client regarding her line of defence.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\" /> The trial judge Tonia Antoniou adjourned the case until 19 August to give the woman time to find a new lawyer. He also remanded the defendant into custody. The defendant was supported by the legal aid group Justice Abroad, which supported her claims that she had been coerced into producing a retraction statement.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Oppenheim |first1=Maya |title=British teenager facing jail for retracting claim of gang rape on holiday loses lawyer |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/cyprus-rape-claim-british-woman-justice-abroad-nicosia-lawyer-quit-a9045106.html |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112024606/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/cyprus-rape-claim-british-woman-justice-abroad-nicosia-lawyer-quit-a9045106.html|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 August, the defendant pleaded not guilty to falsely claiming she was gang-raped and was bailed by a court on condition that she visited a police station in [[Nicosia]] three times a week before her trial.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\" /><ref name=\"Guardian 27 Aug 2019\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Helena |title=British woman denies making up claim she was raped on Cyprus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/aug/27/british-teenager-denies-making-up-claims-raped-cyprus |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=27 Aug 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112041443/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/aug/27/british-teenager-denies-making-up-claims-raped-cyprus|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref> The woman was represented by British lawyer Lewis Power [[Queen's Counsel|QC]] and two Cypriot lawyers, who were supported by Justice Abroad. The defendant had reportedly spent a month at the [[Central Jail of Nicosia]], where she had reportedly shared a cramped cell with nine women.<ref name=\"Telegraph 2 Oct 2019\" /><ref name=\"Guardian trial delay\" /> Michael Polak, the Director of Justice International and a member of the defence team, claimed that the defendant's interrogation violated the [[Constitution of Cyprus]] and [[European Union]] human rights legislation.<ref name=\"Guardian 27 Aug 2019\" />\n\nOn 2 October, the defendant's trial began. While the defence maintained that the woman had been raped and had been coerced into issuing a retraction, the prosecution insisted that the police had acted properly throughout the investigation. Judge Michalis Papathanasiou adjourned the defendant's trial by two weeks to allow the defence to produce new evidence including text messages and images circulated by the alleged attackers to support their contention that she had been raped. The defendant was also reportedly suffering from [[Post-traumatic stress disorder]] due to her legal ordeal.<ref name=\"Telegraph 2 Oct 2019\">{{cite news |last1=Squires |first1=Nick |title=Lawyer reveals 19-year-old British woman 'suffering from PTSD' on first day of trial over Cyprus 'rape' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/02/lawyer-reveals-19-year-old-british-woman-suffering-ptsd-first/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=2 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112033717/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/02/lawyer-reveals-19-year-old-british-woman-suffering-ptsd-first/|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian trial delay\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Helena |title=Delay in trial of UK woman accused of making up rape claims in Cyprus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/02/cyprus-trial-begins-of-british-woman-accused-of-making-up-rape-claim |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2 October 2019|archive-url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/02/cyprus-trial-begins-of-british-woman-accused-of-making-up-rape-claim|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe teenager's trial resumed on 15 October 2019.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\" /> On 28 November, the trial judge Michalis Papathansidi rejected the defence's claim of a forced confession and defended the police investigators who had conducted investigation. He ruled the defendant an \"unreliable witness\", claiming that she had provided the police with \"contradictory, inconsistent, exaggerated and inflated\" versions of the night of the alleged crime. The judge also dismissed the defence witnesses as unreliable and rejected the testimony of expert witnesses from the UK, including a forensic linguistic expert's testimony that the woman's confession was unlikely to have been written by a native English speaker. The trial proceeded with the testimony of police officers who had spoken to her on the night she had reported the alleged sexual assaults.<ref>{{cite news |title=Judge dismisses girl\u2019s claim, she will face trial for public mischief (Update) |url=https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/11/28/judge-dismisses-girls-claim-she-will-face-trial-for-public-mischief/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[Cyprus Mail]] |date=28 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328172649/https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/11/28/judge-dismisses-girls-claim-she-will-face-trial-for-public-mischief/|archive-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Cyprus judge: UK teen not coerced to recant Israeli rape claim, trial to proceed |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/cyprus-judge-uk-teen-not-coerced-to-recant-israeli-rape-claim-trial-to-proceed/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=28 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222131358/https://www.timesofisrael.com/cyprus-judge-uk-teen-not-coerced-to-recant-israeli-rape-claim-trial-to-proceed/|archive-date=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 December 2019, the court heard the defendant's testimony, who maintained that she had been gang-raped by the Israeli youths and that she had been coerced by police into dropping the rape allegations. The case concluded on 6 December with testimony by defence witness, well-known pathologist Marios Matsakis.<ref>{{cite news |title=British teenager details to court her rape by Israeli tourists |url=https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/12/03/british-teenager-details-to-court-her-rape-by-israeli-tourists/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[Cyprus Mail]] |date=3 December 2019}}</ref> On 12 December, the defendant was told that she would have to remain in Cyprus over Christmas, with the final judgment expected on 30 December. On 30 December, the court found the defendant guilty of causing public mischief with her sentencing date set for 7 January 2019. In response, the defence said that they would appeal the verdict.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ensor |first1=Josie |last2=Squires |first2=Nick |title=British teenager found guilty of lying about 'gang rape' in Cyprus holiday resort |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/12/30/british-woman-19-found-guilty-lying-gang-rape-cyprus/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=30 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301191319/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/12/30/british-woman-19-found-guilty-lying-gang-rape-cyprus/|archive-date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 January 2020, the Famagusta District Court released their 70-page verdict defending their guilty verdict in response to criticism of the court's handling of the case from both Cyprus and abroad.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Charalambous |first1=Annie |title=Detailed court ruling explains why British teen was found guilty of lying about gang rape |url=https://in-cyprus.com/detailed-court-ruling-explains-why-british-teen-was-found-guilty-of-lying-about-gang-rape/ |website=In-Cyprus |accessdate=12 January 2020 |date=4 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112041445/https://in-cyprus.com/detailed-court-ruling-explains-why-british-teen-was-found-guilty-of-lying-about-gang-rape/|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref> On 7 January, Judge Papathanasiou sentenced the young woman to a four month suspended sentence, with the defendant being allowed to leave Cyprus.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\">{{cite news |last1=Jacobson |first1=Seth |title=Timeline: the British teenager convicted over rape claims in Cyprus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/30/timeline-the-british-teenager-convicted-over-claims-in-cyprus |accessdate=7 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=30 December 2019|archive-url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/30/timeline-the-british-teenager-convicted-over-claims-in-cyprus|archive-date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC sentenced\">{{cite news |title=Ayia Napa Briton sentenced over false rape claim |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51017485 |accessdate=7 January 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117164251/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51017485|archive-date=17 January 2020}}</ref> In response, the defence announced that they would be appealing the conviction at the [[Supreme Court of Cyprus]], a process expected to take several years.<ref name=\"Telegraph sentencing\">{{cite news |last1=Squires |first1=Nick |title=British teenager in Cyprus gang rape case handed four-month suspended jail sentence |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/07/british-teenager-cyprus-gang-rape-case-handed-four-month-suspended/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305142743/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/07/british-teenager-cyprus-gang-rape-case-handed-four-month-suspended/|archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC sentenced\" /><ref name=\"CNN sentenced\" /><ref name=\"NYT 7 Jan 2020\" />\n\n==Reactions==\nThe Ayia Napa rape allegation case attracted considerable media coverage and commentary in the British and international news media.<ref name=\"Harriet Hall editorial\">{{cite news |last1=Hall |first1=Harriet |title=There is one clear truth in the Ayia Napa rape case \u2013 a young woman\u2019s life has been destroyed |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/ayia-napa-rape-trial-cyprus-israel-metoo-latest-a9274126.html |accessdate=7 January 2020 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330011008/https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/ayia-napa-rape-trial-cyprus-israel-metoo-latest-a9274126.html|archive-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN sentenced\">{{cite news |last1=McKenzie |first1=Sheena |title=British teen sentenced over gang rape claim in Cyprus resort |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/07/europe/ayia-napa-cyprus-british-woman-sentenced-intl/index.html |accessdate=7 January 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319101815/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/07/europe/ayia-napa-cyprus-british-woman-sentenced-intl/index.html|archive-date=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT 7 Jan 2020\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/07/world/europe/cyprus-uk-rape.html|title=British Woman Who Accused Israelis of Rape in Cyprus Is Spared Prison|first1=Lizzy|last1=Ioannidou|first2=Iliana|last2=Magra|date=January 7, 2020|work=[[New York Times]]|access-date=8 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310082326/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/07/world/europe/cyprus-uk-rape.html|archive-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Israeli youths===\nFollowing their release in late July, several of the Israeli teenagers were greeted by their cheering families at [[Ben Gurion International Airport]] in [[Tel Aviv]]. According to media reports, the boys were dressed in [[kippah]]s and they and their male relatives popped champagne, let off a confetti cannon and chanted \"''Am Yisrael Chai''\" (\"the people of Israel lives\") and \"the Brit is a whore.\" This heroes' welcome was criticized by several Israeli journalists, social media users, and parents for engaging in unethical behaviour including filming their sexual encounter with their alleged victim, which is illegal under Israeli law banning \"[[revenge porn]].\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Some in Israel uneasy with heroes\u2019 welcome for teens cleared of gang rape |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/some-in-israel-uneasy-with-heroes-welcome-for-teens-cleared-of-gang-rape/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=29 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191103210921/https://www.timesofisrael.com/some-in-israel-uneasy-with-heroes-welcome-for-teens-cleared-of-gang-rape/|archive-date=3 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Turner |first1=Janice |title=Claim rape and a social media assault begins |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/claim-rape-and-a-social-media-assault-begins-q3rwvchg0 |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |date=4 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305092901/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/claim-rape-and-a-social-media-assault-begins-q3rwvchg0|archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Artzi |first1=Chen Sror |title=The lesson we should all learn from the Cyprus affair |url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5559501,00.html |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[Ynet]] |date=29 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112060638/https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5559501,00.html|archive-date=12 Jan 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Defendant's parents and human rights activists===\nOn 9 August 2019, the British teenager's parents established a [[GoFundMe]] campaign to raise \u20a415,000 (US$18,000) to cover their daughter's legal fees following the resignation of her first lawyer Andreas Pittadjis. Aryeh Fraser, an Israeli man living in Miami, had donated \u00a37,500 (US$9,000) to the GoFundMe campaign, describing it as a humanitarian donation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Israeli man donates $9,000 to UK teen who accused Israelis of rape in Cyprus |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-man-donates-9000-to-uk-teen-who-accused-israelis-of-rape-in-cyprus/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=10 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191130164932/https://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-man-donates-9000-to-uk-teen-who-accused-israelis-of-rape-in-cyprus/|archive-date=30 November 2019}}</ref> By 3 January 2020, the teenager's GoFundMe campaign had reach \u20a4120,000, exceeding its \u20a4105,000 target.<ref name=\"Teen begs for help\">{{cite news |title=Cyprus rape case: Teenager begs Boris Johnson to bring her home and end 'waking nightmare' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/03/cyprus-rape-case-teenager-begs-boris-johnson-bring-home-end/ |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=3 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228233509/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/03/cyprus-rape-case-teenager-begs-boris-johnson-bring-home-end/|archive-date=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, Michael Polak, the director of the legal aid organisation Justice Abroad and a member of the defence team, criticised the Cypriot Police's handling of the investigation into the rape allegations including allegedly coercing a retraction from the defendant without a lawyer present and not making any audio or video recordings of the defendant's interrogation.<ref name=\"Telegraph 2 Oct 2019\" /><ref name=\"Guardian trial delay\" /> He also criticised the Cypriot Police for failing to download data from the alleged Israeli attackers' 11 mobile phones; the Police had downloaded videos from five of the Israeli youths' phones but had neglected to collect text messages and social media data.<ref name=\"Telegraph 2 Oct 2019\" />\n\nOn 14 October, several human rights and feminist groups urged the Cypriot [[attorney general]] [[Costas Clerides]] to dismiss the case against the British teenager. Susana Pavlou, the Director of the Mediterranean Institute for Gender Studies, criticized the brutal ordeal experienced by the British teenager and her family.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Squires |first1=Nick |title=British teenager tells court she 'couldn't breathe' during alleged Cyprus gang-rape by Israeli tourists |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/12/03/british-teenager-describes-cyprus-court-gang-raped-assault/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=3 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109001752/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/12/03/british-teenager-describes-cyprus-court-gang-raped-assault/|archive-date=9 January 2020}}</ref> Several Cypriot and Israeli feminists and women's rights activists also picketed the sentencing of the defendant on 7 January 2020, criticizing Judge Papathanasiou for [[victim blaming]] and siding with the alleged rapists.<ref name=\"Telegraph sentencing\" /><ref name=\"BBC sentenced\" /><ref name=\"CNN sentenced\" />\n\n===Governmental responses===\nThe United Kingdom Government has also raised concerns about the fairness of the teenager's trial in Cyprus. In response to the British teenager's guilty verdict, a British [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] spokesperson issued a statement on 30 December 2019 that \"the UK is seriously concerned about the fair trial guarantees in this deeply distressing case and we will be raising the issue with the Cypriot authorities.\"<ref name=\"Cyprus Mail 30 Dec 2019\">{{cite news |last1=Christou |first1=Jean |title=UK govt to question woman's guilty verdict in Napa rape claim case, defence to appeal (Update 7) |url=https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/12/30/uk-govt-to-question-womans-guilty-verdict-in-napa-rape-claim-case-defence-to-appeal-update-7/ |accessdate=7 January 2020 |work=[[Cyprus Mail]] |date=30 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329144140/https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/12/30/uk-govt-to-question-womans-guilty-verdict-in-napa-rape-claim-case-defence-to-appeal-update-7/|archive-date=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian UK raises concerns\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Helena |title=UK raises concerns with Cyprus over teenager convicted of lying about rape |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/dec/30/briton-found-guilty-over-ayia-napa-false-claim-cyprus |accessdate=7 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=31 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206023407/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/dec/30/briton-found-guilty-over-ayia-napa-false-claim-cyprus|archive-date=6 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN 31 Dec 2019\">{{cite news |last1=Dewan |first1=Angela |last2=Siad |first2=Arnaud |last3=Braithwaite |first3=Sharon |title=UK to press Cyprus on 'distressing' teen gang rape case |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/12/31/europe/ayia-napa-cyprus-gang-rape-case-uk-gbr-intl/index.html |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=31 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111153817/https://edition.cnn.com/2019/12/31/europe/ayia-napa-cyprus-gang-rape-case-uk-gbr-intl/index.html|archive-date=11 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Sky News\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/british-woman-found-guilty-of-lying-about-cyprus-gang-rape-11897959|title=UK to raise concerns with Cyprus after British teen is found guilty of false rape claim|work=[[Sky News]]|access-date=8 January 2020|date=1 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204061419/https://news.sky.com/story/british-woman-found-guilty-of-lying-about-cyprus-gang-rape-11897959|archive-date=4 February 2020}}</ref> The British [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] [[Dominic Raab]] also stated that the UK Government was examining guidelines for British tourists to Cyprus in light of the rape allegation case.<ref name=\"Haaretz 6 Jan 2020\">{{cite news |last1=Shpigel |first1=Noa |title=Cypriot President to Pardon British Woman in Gang Rape Case, Reports Say |url=https://www.haaretz.com/world-news/europe/.premium-cypriot-president-to-pardon-british-woman-in-gang-rape-case-reports-say-1.8368572 |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[Haaretz]] |date=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330090623/https://www.haaretz.com/world-news/europe/.premium-cypriot-president-to-pardon-british-woman-in-gang-rape-case-reports-say-1.8368572|archive-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Raab later welcomed the British teenager's suspended jail term sentence but ruled our revising British tourism guidelines to Cyprus.<ref>{{cite news |title=UK Foreign Minister relieved rape-claim woman not jailed |url=https://www.financialmirror.com/2020/01/07/uk-foreign-minister-relieved-rape-claim-woman-not-jailed/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[Financial Mirror]] |date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112065214/https://www.financialmirror.com/2020/01/07/uk-foreign-minister-relieved-rape-claim-woman-not-jailed/|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn early January 2020, there were media reports that the [[President of Cyprus]] [[Nicos Anastasiades]] was considering pardoning the British teenager prior to her sentencing on 7 January.<ref name=\"Haaretz 6 Jan 2020\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Oppenheim |first1=Maya |title=Cyprus rape case: President urged to intervene after British woman found guilty of lying about attack |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/cyprus-rape-case-british-woman-president-aiya-napa-lie-trial-sentence-a9267566.html |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=2 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227075443/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/cyprus-rape-case-british-woman-president-aiya-napa-lie-trial-sentence-a9267566.html|archive-date=27 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=UK woman in Ayia Napa rape case to be pardoned by Cyprus president: report |url=https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/UK-woman-in-Ayia-Napa-rape-case-to-be-pardoned-by-Cyprus-president-report-613304 |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112065212/https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/UK-woman-in-Ayia-Napa-rape-case-to-be-pardoned-by-Cyprus-president-report-613304|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Boycott Cyprus campaign===\nIn January 2020, a campaign was launched on the social media platform [[Twitter]] with the hashtag #boycottcyprus.<ref>{{cite web |title=#boycottcyprus |url=https://twitter.com/hashtag/boycottcyprus?src=hashtag_click |publisher=[[Twitter]] |accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Theodoulou |first1=Nick |title=Could controversial Napa rape claim conviction hit tourism? |url=https://cyprus-mail.com/2020/01/04/could-controversial-napa-rape-claim-conviction-hit-tourism/ |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=[[Cyprus Mail]] |date=4 January 2020}}</ref> On 1 January, the British teenager's mother expressed support for a boycott campaign against Cyprus, stating that the country was unsafe for tourists and condemning her daughter's guilty verdict as a miscarriage if justice.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayia Napa: Mother of convicted Briton backs Cyprus boycott |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-50963049 |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=1 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109022025/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-50963049|archive-date=9 January 2020}}</ref> On 6 January, protesters expressing support for the teenager picketed the Cypriot High Commission in London. In addition, solidarity protests with the teenager were also planned in Nicosia and Tel Aviv to time with the teenager's sentencing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gayle |first1=Damien |last2=Smith |first2=Helena |title=Protesters in London call for Cyprus boycott on eve of sentencing |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/06/protesters-in-london-call-for-cyprus-boycott-on-eve-of-sentencing |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216192955/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/06/protesters-in-london-call-for-cyprus-boycott-on-eve-of-sentencing|archive-date=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 January 2020, Summer Takeaways, the tour company behind the working holiday in which the British defendant had been allegedly gang raped, announced that the company would no longer provide services to Ayia Napa. The company removed all references to Ayia Napa on its website and offered refunds to customers who had booked for the upcoming 2020 summer tour to the destination.<ref name=\"UK tour firm Guardian\" /><ref name=\"Telegraph holiday firm\" />\n\n===Media commentary===\n''The Independent''{{'s}} columnist Harriet Hall opined that the Ayia Napa rape case reflected a long tradition of ignoring or punishing female rape victims.<ref name=\"Harriet Hall editorial\" />\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2010s crimes in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:2019 in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Sexual misconduct allegations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=January 2020}}\nThe '''2019 Cyprus rape allegation case''' was a high-profile case of alleged gang rape in [[Cyprus]]. In July 2019, a British woman on vacation in [[Ayia Napa]] alleged she had been gang raped by twelve Israeli tourists. The Israeli men were subsequently arrested and investigated over the allegation by the [[Cyprus Police]], but they were subsequently released without charge and the woman was detained for making a false allegation after she retracted her statement. In January 2020, the woman was convicted of \"public mischief\" in a Cypriot court and received a suspended sentence. The case triggered international concerns about the way the case had been handled by the Cypriot authorities. The woman has maintained that she was forced to retract her statement under pressure, something contested by Cypriot authorities. \n\n==Alleged crime and police investigation==\nDuring the 2019 summer break, the 19-year old British woman had traveled to Pambos Napa Rocks resort in the Cypriot resort town of [[Ayia Napa]] on a working holiday organised by the British tourism company Summer Takeaways.<ref name=\"UK tour firm Guardian\">{{cite news |last1=Halliday |first1=Josh |last2=Smith |first2=Helena |title=UK tour firm used by teenager in gang rape case ends trips to Ayia Napa |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/jan/03/uk-tour-firm-used-teenager-gang-case-ends-trips-ayia-napa |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=3 January 2020|archive-url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/jan/03/uk-tour-firm-used-teenager-gang-case-ends-trips-ayia-napa|archive-date=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Telegraph holiday firm\">{{cite news |title=UK working holiday firm ends Ayia Napa trips over rape claim |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/03/uk-working-holiday-firm-ends-ayia-napa-trips-rape-claim/ |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=3 January 2020}}</ref> On 17 July 2019, the British teenager filed a report with the Cyprus Police in Ayia Napa claiming that she had been raped by several Israeli youths in her hotel room. The following day, the Cypriot authorities arrested 12 Israeli youths, aged between 15 and 22 years, for eight days. The police investigation was led by Detective Sergeant Marios Christou. Police questioned the suspects and took DNA samples from all twelve. Police found five used condoms and thirteen condom wrappers in the room.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cypriot police question Israeli suspects in alleged gang rape |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/cypriot-police-question-israeli-suspects-in-alleged-gang-rape/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=20 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://www.timesofisrael.com/cypriot-police-question-israeli-suspects-in-alleged-gang-rape |archivedate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe woman was examined by Cypriot state pathologist Dr. Sophocles Sophocleus, who found no evidence of gang rape. He subsequently testified that he found a few light bruises on her thighs and scratches on her legs but in his opinion, they were not consistent with gang rape. He also examined the woman's vagina together with a gynecologist and reported finding no lesions or other injuries.<ref>{{cite news |title=British teenager in gang rape case had no serious physical injuries, doctor tells Cyprus court |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/29/british-teenager-gang-rape-case-had-no-serious-physical-injuries/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=29 November 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217093447/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/29/british-teenager-gang-rape-case-had-no-serious-physical-injuries/ |archivedate=17 February 2020}}</ref> However, private forensic pathologist Dr. [[Marios Matsakis]], who was hired by her family to participate in the case, reported that there was clear evidence of gang rape. Later testifying for her defense at trial, he stated he found bruising across her legs, arms, and buttocks from photographs of her injuries shown in court, claiming that he identified 35 separate bruises, and that the injuries left \"no doubt\" of gang rape.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayia Napa teen 'who made up rape' had 35 bruises that judge said were 'jellyfish stings' |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/ayia-napa-teen-who-made-21216145 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=5 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217093447/https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/ayia-napa-teen-who-made-21216145 |archivedate=17 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dillon |first1=Nancy |title=British teen convicted of lying about gang rape by Israeli men in Cyprus, vows appeal |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/ny-british-woman-plans-tappeal-verdict-she-lied-about-cyprus-gang-rape-20191230-6evewm2stbhhlbt42wujlx7vhu-story.html |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[New York Daily News]] |date=30 December 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217093447/https://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/ny-british-woman-plans-tappeal-verdict-she-lied-about-cyprus-gang-rape-20191230-6evewm2stbhhlbt42wujlx7vhu-story.html |archivedate=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>https://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/ny-british-woman-plans-tappeal-verdict-she-lied-about-cyprus-gang-rape-20191230-6evewm2stbhhlbt42wujlx7vhu-story.html</ref> He also criticized Sophocleus for allegedly improperly investigating her. \n\nOn 25 July, five of the youths were released due to a lack of DNA evidence connecting them to the alleged incident.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\" /> Seven remained detained. In addition to the allegation of gang rape, they were suspected of conspiracy to commit a crime, including those whose DNA was not found on the complainant.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Blumenthal |first1=Itay |title=Israeli teens arrested for gang-rape in Cyprus also suspected of conspiracy to commit crime |url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5555394,00.html |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[Ynet]] |publisher=[[Yedioth Ahronot]] |date=22 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217093447/https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5555394,00.html |archivedate=17 February 2020}}</ref> Following DNA testing, police linked three of the detained to the case and also found three more DNA samples not matching any of the accused. Police suspected that three Israelis had participated but had subsequently returned to Israel, and prepared to send a team to Israel to work in coordination with the [[Israel Police]] and Israeli travel agencies to identify them.<ref>{{cite news |title=After DNA tests, Cyprus police think 3 further gang rape suspects fled to Israel |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/after-dna-tests-cyprus-police-think-3-further-gang-rape-suspects-fled-to-israel/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=26 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191018164033/https://www.timesofisrael.com/after-dna-tests-cyprus-police-think-3-further-gang-rape-suspects-fled-to-israel/ |archivedate=26 July 2019}}</ref> On 27 July, it was reported that three of the suspects were set to be charged, with police likely to release at least two other suspects. There were conflicting reports over whether or not police would offer immunity from prosecution to one or two of the suspects in exchange for information on other suspects still being sought. Police said they have taken statements from 36 witnesses and that they were planning to interview 20 more.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cypriot police said set to charge at least 3 Israeli teens in gang rape case |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/cypriot-police-said-set-to-charge-at-least-3-israeli-teens-in-gang-rape-case/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=27 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209084342/https://www.timesofisrael.com/cypriot-police-said-set-to-charge-at-least-3-israeli-teens-in-gang-rape-case/ |archivedate=9 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the investigation turned toward the British woman. According to an attorney for some of the Israelis, they were able to provide convincing evidence of their innocence.<ref>{{cite news |title=All Israeli suspects in Cyprus gang rape released; British complainant arrested |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/all-israeli-suspects-in-cyprus-gang-rape-to-be-released-lawyer-says/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=28 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223174445/https://www.timesofisrael.com/all-israeli-suspects-in-cyprus-gang-rape-to-be-released-lawyer-says/ |archivedate=23 February 2020}}</ref> On 27 July, the British teenager visited a police station to give a statement but was instead accused of lying about allegations. Following eight hours of questioning without a lawyer, the woman signed a statement retracting her rape allegations:\n<blockquote>The report I did on the 17th of July 2019 that I was raped at ayia napa was not the truth. The truth is that I wasnt raped and everything that happened in that appartment was with my consent. The reason I made the statement with the fake report is because I did not know they were recording & humiliating me that night I discovered them recording me doing sexual intercourse and I felt embarrassed as I want to appologise, and say I made a mistake.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Morley |first1=Nathan |title=Linguist casts doubt on rape retraction statement |url=https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/11/15/linguist-casts-doubt-on-rape-retraction-statement/ |accessdate=16 January 2020 |work=[[Cyprus Mail]] |date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ames |first1=Jonathan |title=Cyprus rape case: Experts cast doubt on teenager\u2019s confession |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/cyprus-rape-case-experts-cast-doubt-on-teenagers-confession-x8r9s3xcc |accessdate=16 January 2020 |work=[[The Times]] |date=3 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325161923/https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/11/15/linguist-casts-doubt-on-rape-retraction-statement/|archive-date=25 March 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\nThe defence has contended that the defendant made the statement while under duress. Cypriot authorities charged her with \"giving a false statement over an imaginary offence.\" On 28 July, the remaining Israeli suspects were released from custody.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\" /> Cypriot Police claimed that the woman had got angry when her alleged attackers had filmed her having consensual sex with some of the alleged attackers and alleged she had been raped. Nir Yaslovitch, a lawyer representing several of the Israeli youths, said that his clients would seek legal damages against her for false rape allegations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elizera |first1=Rotem |title=All Israeli teens in Cyprus rape case freed as British accuser arrested |url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5558680,00.html |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[Ynet]] |date=28 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112025311/https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5558680,00.html|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hadjicostis |first1=Menelaos |title=7 Israeli Teens Freed After Woman Recants Cyprus Rape Report |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-28/lawyer-cyprus-will-free-7-israelis-detained-in-rape-case |accessdate=12 January 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |date=28 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112024609/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-28/lawyer-cyprus-will-free-7-israelis-detained-in-rape-case|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legal proceedings==\nOn 30 July, the woman appeared at the Famagusta District Court in [[Paralimni]], where she was charged with acts of \"public mischief\" and remanded into custody for eight days.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\" /> On 6 August 2019, the defendant repudiated her retraction statement, claiming that she had been coerced into producing it by the Cypriot Police. Her lawyer Andreas Pittadjis resigned due to a \"serious disagreement\" with his client regarding her line of defence.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\" /> The trial judge Tonia Antoniou adjourned the case until 19 August to give the woman time to find a new lawyer. He also remanded the defendant into custody. The defendant was supported by the legal aid group Justice Abroad, which supported her claims that she had been coerced into producing a retraction statement.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Oppenheim |first1=Maya |title=British teenager facing jail for retracting claim of gang rape on holiday loses lawyer |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/cyprus-rape-claim-british-woman-justice-abroad-nicosia-lawyer-quit-a9045106.html |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=7 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112024606/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/cyprus-rape-claim-british-woman-justice-abroad-nicosia-lawyer-quit-a9045106.html|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 August, the defendant pleaded not guilty to falsely claiming she was gang-raped and was bailed by a court on condition that she visited a police station in [[Nicosia]] three times a week before her trial.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\" /><ref name=\"Guardian 27 Aug 2019\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Helena |title=British woman denies making up claim she was raped on Cyprus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/aug/27/british-teenager-denies-making-up-claims-raped-cyprus |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=27 Aug 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112041443/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/aug/27/british-teenager-denies-making-up-claims-raped-cyprus|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref> The woman was represented by British lawyer Lewis Power [[Queen's Counsel|QC]] and two Cypriot lawyers, who were supported by Justice Abroad. The defendant had reportedly spent a month at the [[Central Jail of Nicosia]], where she had reportedly shared a cramped cell with nine women.<ref name=\"Telegraph 2 Oct 2019\" /><ref name=\"Guardian trial delay\" /> Michael Polak, the Director of Justice International and a member of the defence team, claimed that the defendant's interrogation violated the [[Constitution of Cyprus]] and [[European Union]] human rights legislation.<ref name=\"Guardian 27 Aug 2019\" />\n\nOn 2 October, the defendant's trial began. While the defence maintained that the woman had been raped and had been coerced into issuing a retraction, the prosecution insisted that the police had acted properly throughout the investigation. Judge Michalis Papathanasiou adjourned the defendant's trial by two weeks to allow the defence to produce new evidence including text messages and images circulated by the alleged attackers to support their contention that she had been raped. The defendant was also reportedly suffering from [[Post-traumatic stress disorder]] due to her legal ordeal.<ref name=\"Telegraph 2 Oct 2019\">{{cite news |last1=Squires |first1=Nick |title=Lawyer reveals 19-year-old British woman 'suffering from PTSD' on first day of trial over Cyprus 'rape' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/02/lawyer-reveals-19-year-old-british-woman-suffering-ptsd-first/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=2 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112033717/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/02/lawyer-reveals-19-year-old-british-woman-suffering-ptsd-first/|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian trial delay\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Helena |title=Delay in trial of UK woman accused of making up rape claims in Cyprus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/02/cyprus-trial-begins-of-british-woman-accused-of-making-up-rape-claim |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2 October 2019|archive-url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/02/cyprus-trial-begins-of-british-woman-accused-of-making-up-rape-claim|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe teenager's trial resumed on 15 October 2019.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\" /> On 28 November, the trial judge Michalis Papathansidi rejected the defence's claim of a forced confession and defended the police investigators who had conducted investigation. He ruled the defendant an \"unreliable witness\", claiming that she had provided the police with \"contradictory, inconsistent, exaggerated and inflated\" versions of the night of the alleged crime. The judge also dismissed the defence witnesses as unreliable and rejected the testimony of expert witnesses from the UK, including a forensic linguistic expert's testimony that the woman's confession was unlikely to have been written by a native English speaker. The trial proceeded with the testimony of police officers who had spoken to her on the night she had reported the alleged sexual assaults.<ref>{{cite news |title=Judge dismisses girl\u2019s claim, she will face trial for public mischief (Update) |url=https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/11/28/judge-dismisses-girls-claim-she-will-face-trial-for-public-mischief/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[Cyprus Mail]] |date=28 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328172649/https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/11/28/judge-dismisses-girls-claim-she-will-face-trial-for-public-mischief/|archive-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Cyprus judge: UK teen not coerced to recant Israeli rape claim, trial to proceed |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/cyprus-judge-uk-teen-not-coerced-to-recant-israeli-rape-claim-trial-to-proceed/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=28 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222131358/https://www.timesofisrael.com/cyprus-judge-uk-teen-not-coerced-to-recant-israeli-rape-claim-trial-to-proceed/|archive-date=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 December 2019, the court heard the defendant's testimony, who maintained that she had been gang-raped by the Israeli youths and that she had been coerced by police into dropping the rape allegations. The case concluded on 6 December with testimony by defence witness, well-known pathologist Marios Matsakis.<ref>{{cite news |title=British teenager details to court her rape by Israeli tourists |url=https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/12/03/british-teenager-details-to-court-her-rape-by-israeli-tourists/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[Cyprus Mail]] |date=3 December 2019}}</ref> On 12 December, the defendant was told that she would have to remain in Cyprus over Christmas, with the final judgment expected on 30 December. On 30 December, the court found the defendant guilty of causing public mischief with her sentencing date set for 7 January 2019. In response, the defence said that they would appeal the verdict.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ensor |first1=Josie |last2=Squires |first2=Nick |title=British teenager found guilty of lying about 'gang rape' in Cyprus holiday resort |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/12/30/british-woman-19-found-guilty-lying-gang-rape-cyprus/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=30 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301191319/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/12/30/british-woman-19-found-guilty-lying-gang-rape-cyprus/|archive-date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 January 2020, the Famagusta District Court released their 70-page verdict defending their guilty verdict in response to criticism of the court's handling of the case from both Cyprus and abroad.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Charalambous |first1=Annie |title=Detailed court ruling explains why British teen was found guilty of lying about gang rape |url=https://in-cyprus.com/detailed-court-ruling-explains-why-british-teen-was-found-guilty-of-lying-about-gang-rape/ |website=In-Cyprus |accessdate=12 January 2020 |date=4 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112041445/https://in-cyprus.com/detailed-court-ruling-explains-why-british-teen-was-found-guilty-of-lying-about-gang-rape/|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref> On 7 January, Judge Papathanasiou sentenced the young woman to a four month suspended sentence, with the defendant being allowed to leave Cyprus.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\">{{cite news |last1=Jacobson |first1=Seth |title=Timeline: the British teenager convicted over rape claims in Cyprus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/30/timeline-the-british-teenager-convicted-over-claims-in-cyprus |accessdate=7 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=30 December 2019|archive-url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/30/timeline-the-british-teenager-convicted-over-claims-in-cyprus|archive-date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC sentenced\">{{cite news |title=Ayia Napa Briton sentenced over false rape claim |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51017485 |accessdate=7 January 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117164251/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51017485|archive-date=17 January 2020}}</ref> In response, the defence announced that they would be appealing the conviction at the [[Supreme Court of Cyprus]], a process expected to take several years.<ref name=\"Telegraph sentencing\">{{cite news |last1=Squires |first1=Nick |title=British teenager in Cyprus gang rape case handed four-month suspended jail sentence |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/07/british-teenager-cyprus-gang-rape-case-handed-four-month-suspended/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305142743/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/07/british-teenager-cyprus-gang-rape-case-handed-four-month-suspended/|archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC sentenced\" /><ref name=\"CNN sentenced\" /><ref name=\"NYT 7 Jan 2020\" />\n\n==Reactions==\nThe Ayia Napa rape allegation case attracted considerable media coverage and commentary in the British and international news media.<ref name=\"Harriet Hall editorial\">{{cite news |last1=Hall |first1=Harriet |title=There is one clear truth in the Ayia Napa rape case \u2013 a young woman\u2019s life has been destroyed |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/ayia-napa-rape-trial-cyprus-israel-metoo-latest-a9274126.html |accessdate=7 January 2020 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330011008/https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/ayia-napa-rape-trial-cyprus-israel-metoo-latest-a9274126.html|archive-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN sentenced\">{{cite news |last1=McKenzie |first1=Sheena |title=British teen sentenced over gang rape claim in Cyprus resort |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/07/europe/ayia-napa-cyprus-british-woman-sentenced-intl/index.html |accessdate=7 January 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319101815/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/07/europe/ayia-napa-cyprus-british-woman-sentenced-intl/index.html|archive-date=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT 7 Jan 2020\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/07/world/europe/cyprus-uk-rape.html|title=British Woman Who Accused Israelis of Rape in Cyprus Is Spared Prison|first1=Lizzy|last1=Ioannidou|first2=Iliana|last2=Magra|date=January 7, 2020|work=[[New York Times]]|access-date=8 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310082326/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/07/world/europe/cyprus-uk-rape.html|archive-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Israeli youths===\nFollowing their release in late July, several of the Israeli teenagers were greeted by their cheering families at [[Ben Gurion International Airport]] in [[Tel Aviv]]. According to media reports, the boys were dressed in [[kippah]]s and they and their male relatives popped champagne, let off a confetti cannon and chanted \"''Am Yisrael Chai''\" (\"the people of Israel lives\") and \"the Brit is a whore.\" This heroes' welcome was criticized by several Israeli journalists, social media users, and parents for engaging in unethical behaviour including filming their sexual encounter with their alleged victim, which is illegal under Israeli law banning \"[[revenge porn]].\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Some in Israel uneasy with heroes\u2019 welcome for teens cleared of gang rape |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/some-in-israel-uneasy-with-heroes-welcome-for-teens-cleared-of-gang-rape/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=29 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191103210921/https://www.timesofisrael.com/some-in-israel-uneasy-with-heroes-welcome-for-teens-cleared-of-gang-rape/|archive-date=3 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Turner |first1=Janice |title=Claim rape and a social media assault begins |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/claim-rape-and-a-social-media-assault-begins-q3rwvchg0 |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |date=4 January 2020}|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305092901/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/claim-rape-and-a-social-media-assault-begins-q3rwvchg0|archive-date=5 March 2020}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Artzi |first1=Chen Sror |title=The lesson we should all learn from the Cyprus affair |url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5559501,00.html |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[Ynet]] |date=29 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112060638/https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5559501,00.html|archive-date=12 Jan 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Defendant's parents and human rights activists===\nOn 9 August 2019, the British teenager's parents established a [[GoFundMe]] campaign to raise \u20a415,000 (US$18,000) to cover their daughter's legal fees following the resignation of her first lawyer Andreas Pittadjis. Aryeh Fraser, an Israeli man living in Miami, had donated \u00a37,500 (US$9,000) to the GoFundMe campaign, describing it as a humanitarian donation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Israeli man donates $9,000 to UK teen who accused Israelis of rape in Cyprus |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-man-donates-9000-to-uk-teen-who-accused-israelis-of-rape-in-cyprus/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=10 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191130164932/https://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-man-donates-9000-to-uk-teen-who-accused-israelis-of-rape-in-cyprus/|archive-date=30 November 2019}}</ref> By 3 January 2020, the teenager's GoFundMe campaign had reach \u20a4120,000, exceeding its \u20a4105,000 target.<ref name=\"Teen begs for help\">{{cite news |title=Cyprus rape case: Teenager begs Boris Johnson to bring her home and end 'waking nightmare' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/03/cyprus-rape-case-teenager-begs-boris-johnson-bring-home-end/ |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=3 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228233509/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/03/cyprus-rape-case-teenager-begs-boris-johnson-bring-home-end/|archive-date=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, Michael Polak, the director of the legal aid organisation Justice Abroad and a member of the defence team, criticised the Cypriot Police's handling of the investigation into the rape allegations including allegedly coercing a retraction from the defendant without a lawyer present and not making any audio or video recordings of the defendant's interrogation.<ref name=\"Telegraph 2 Oct 2019\" /><ref name=\"Guardian trial delay\" /> He also criticised the Cypriot Police for failing to download data from the alleged Israeli attackers' 11 mobile phones; the Police had downloaded videos from five of the Israeli youths' phones but had neglected to collect text messages and social media data.<ref name=\"Telegraph 2 Oct 2019\" />\n\nOn 14 October, several human rights and feminist groups urged the Cypriot [[attorney general]] [[Costas Clerides]] to dismiss the case against the British teenager. Susana Pavlou, the Director of the Mediterranean Institute for Gender Studies, criticized the brutal ordeal experienced by the British teenager and her family.<ref name=\"Guardian Timeline\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Squires |first1=Nick |title=British teenager tells court she 'couldn't breathe' during alleged Cyprus gang-rape by Israeli tourists |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/12/03/british-teenager-describes-cyprus-court-gang-raped-assault/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=3 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109001752/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/12/03/british-teenager-describes-cyprus-court-gang-raped-assault/|archive-date=9 January 2020}}</ref> Several Cypriot and Israeli feminists and women's rights activists also picketed the sentencing of the defendant on 7 January 2020, criticizing Judge Papathanasiou for [[victim blaming]] and siding with the alleged rapists.<ref name=\"Telegraph sentencing\" /><ref name=\"BBC sentenced\" /><ref name=\"CNN sentenced\" />\n\n===Governmental responses===\nThe United Kingdom Government has also raised concerns about the fairness of the teenager's trial in Cyprus. In response to the British teenager's guilty verdict, a British [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] spokesperson issued a statement on 30 December 2019 that \"the UK is seriously concerned about the fair trial guarantees in this deeply distressing case and we will be raising the issue with the Cypriot authorities.\"<ref name=\"Cyprus Mail 30 Dec 2019\">{{cite news |last1=Christou |first1=Jean |title=UK govt to question woman's guilty verdict in Napa rape claim case, defence to appeal (Update 7) |url=https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/12/30/uk-govt-to-question-womans-guilty-verdict-in-napa-rape-claim-case-defence-to-appeal-update-7/ |accessdate=7 January 2020 |work=[[Cyprus Mail]] |date=30 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329144140/https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/12/30/uk-govt-to-question-womans-guilty-verdict-in-napa-rape-claim-case-defence-to-appeal-update-7/|archive-date=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian UK raises concerns\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Helena |title=UK raises concerns with Cyprus over teenager convicted of lying about rape |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/dec/30/briton-found-guilty-over-ayia-napa-false-claim-cyprus |accessdate=7 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=31 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206023407/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/dec/30/briton-found-guilty-over-ayia-napa-false-claim-cyprus|archive-date=6 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN 31 Dec 2019\">{{cite news |last1=Dewan |first1=Angela |last2=Siad |first2=Arnaud |last3=Braithwaite |first3=Sharon |title=UK to press Cyprus on 'distressing' teen gang rape case |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/12/31/europe/ayia-napa-cyprus-gang-rape-case-uk-gbr-intl/index.html |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=31 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111153817/https://edition.cnn.com/2019/12/31/europe/ayia-napa-cyprus-gang-rape-case-uk-gbr-intl/index.html|archive-date=11 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Sky News\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/british-woman-found-guilty-of-lying-about-cyprus-gang-rape-11897959|title=UK to raise concerns with Cyprus after British teen is found guilty of false rape claim|work=[[Sky News]]|access-date=8 January 2020|date=1 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204061419/https://news.sky.com/story/british-woman-found-guilty-of-lying-about-cyprus-gang-rape-11897959|archive-date=4 February 2020}}</ref> The British [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] [[Dominic Raab]] also stated that the UK Government was examining guidelines for British tourists to Cyprus in light of the rape allegation case.<ref name=\"Haaretz 6 Jan 2020\">{{cite news |last1=Shpigel |first1=Noa |title=Cypriot President to Pardon British Woman in Gang Rape Case, Reports Say |url=https://www.haaretz.com/world-news/europe/.premium-cypriot-president-to-pardon-british-woman-in-gang-rape-case-reports-say-1.8368572 |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[Haaretz]] |date=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330090623/https://www.haaretz.com/world-news/europe/.premium-cypriot-president-to-pardon-british-woman-in-gang-rape-case-reports-say-1.8368572|archive-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Raab later welcomed the British teenager's suspended jail term sentence but ruled our revising British tourism guidelines to Cyprus.<ref>{{cite news |title=UK Foreign Minister relieved rape-claim woman not jailed |url=https://www.financialmirror.com/2020/01/07/uk-foreign-minister-relieved-rape-claim-woman-not-jailed/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[Financial Mirror]] |date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112065214/https://www.financialmirror.com/2020/01/07/uk-foreign-minister-relieved-rape-claim-woman-not-jailed/|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn early January 2020, there were media reports that the [[President of Cyprus]] [[Nicos Anastasiades]] was considering pardoning the British teenager prior to her sentencing on 7 January.<ref name=\"Haaretz 6 Jan 2020\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Oppenheim |first1=Maya |title=Cyprus rape case: President urged to intervene after British woman found guilty of lying about attack |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/cyprus-rape-case-british-woman-president-aiya-napa-lie-trial-sentence-a9267566.html |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=2 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227075443/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/cyprus-rape-case-british-woman-president-aiya-napa-lie-trial-sentence-a9267566.html|archive-date=27 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=UK woman in Ayia Napa rape case to be pardoned by Cyprus president: report |url=https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/UK-woman-in-Ayia-Napa-rape-case-to-be-pardoned-by-Cyprus-president-report-613304 |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112065212/https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/UK-woman-in-Ayia-Napa-rape-case-to-be-pardoned-by-Cyprus-president-report-613304|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Boycott Cyprus campaign===\nIn January 2020, a campaign was launched on the social media platform [[Twitter]] with the hashtag #boycottcyprus.<ref>{{cite web |title=#boycottcyprus |url=https://twitter.com/hashtag/boycottcyprus?src=hashtag_click |publisher=[[Twitter]] |accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Theodoulou |first1=Nick |title=Could controversial Napa rape claim conviction hit tourism? |url=https://cyprus-mail.com/2020/01/04/could-controversial-napa-rape-claim-conviction-hit-tourism/ |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=[[Cyprus Mail]] |date=4 January 2020}}</ref> On 1 January, the British teenager's mother expressed support for a boycott campaign against Cyprus, stating that the country was unsafe for tourists and condemning her daughter's guilty verdict as a miscarriage if justice.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayia Napa: Mother of convicted Briton backs Cyprus boycott |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-50963049 |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=1 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109022025/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-50963049|archive-date=9 January 2020}}</ref> On 6 January, protesters expressing support for the teenager picketed the Cypriot High Commission in London. In addition, solidarity protests with the teenager were also planned in Nicosia and Tel Aviv to time with the teenager's sentencing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gayle |first1=Damien |last2=Smith |first2=Helena |title=Protesters in London call for Cyprus boycott on eve of sentencing |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/06/protesters-in-london-call-for-cyprus-boycott-on-eve-of-sentencing |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=6 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216192955/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/06/protesters-in-london-call-for-cyprus-boycott-on-eve-of-sentencing|archive-date=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 January 2020, Summer Takeaways, the tour company behind the working holiday in which the British defendant had been allegedly gang raped, announced that the company would no longer provide services to Ayia Napa. The company removed all references to Ayia Napa on its website and offered refunds to customers who had booked for the upcoming 2020 summer tour to the destination.<ref name=\"UK tour firm Guardian\" /><ref name=\"Telegraph holiday firm\" />\n\n===Media commentary===\n''The Independent''{{'s}} columnist Harriet Hall opined that the Ayia Napa rape case reflected a long tradition of ignoring or punishing female rape victims.<ref name=\"Harriet Hall editorial\" />\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2010s crimes in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:2019 in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Sexual misconduct allegations]]\n", "name_user": "Andykatib", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIsraeli youths", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_Cyprus_rape_allegation_case"}
{"title_page": "Gavojdia", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Timi\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Timi\u0219 County\n|name=Gavojdia\n|leader_name= D\u0103nu\u021b Toma Stoica\n|leader_party= PNL\n|image_map              = Gavojdia jud Timis.png\n|coordinates = {{coord|45|37|N|22|1|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Gavojdia''' ({{lang-de|Gawoschdia}}; {{lang-hu|Gavosdia}}) is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] in [[Timi\u0219 County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of four villages: Gavojdia, Jena (''Zs\u00e9na''), Lugojel (''Lugoshely'') and S\u0103lb\u0103gel (''Szilv\u00e1shely'').\n\n{{Timi\u0219 County}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Timi\u0219 County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Romanian Banat]]\n\n\n{{Timi\u0219-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Timi\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Timi\u0219 County\n|name=Gavojdia\n|leader_name= D\u0103nu\u021b Toma Stoica\n|leader_party= [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|PNL]]\n|image_map=\n|coordinates = {{coord|45|37|N|22|1|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Gavojdia''' ({{lang-de|Gawoschdia}}; {{lang-hu|Gavosdia}}) is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] in [[Timi\u0219 County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of four villages: Gavojdia, Jena (''Zs\u00e9na''), Lugojel (''Lugoshely'') and S\u0103lb\u0103gel (''Szilv\u00e1shely'').\n\n{{Timi\u0219 County}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Timi\u0219 County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Romanian Banat]]\n\n\n{{Timi\u0219-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gavojdia"}
{"title_page": "Advanced Placement exams", "text_new": "{{Advanced Placement}}\n'''Advanced Placement examinations''' are [[exam]]s offered by the [[College Board]] and are taken each May by students.  The tests are the culmination of year-long [[Advanced Placement|Advanced Placement (AP)]] courses.  AP exams (with few exceptions<ref>[http://www.collegeboard.org CollegeBoard]</ref>) have a multiple-choice section and a free-response section.\n\n[[AP Studio Art]] requires students to submit a [[Career portfolio|portfolio]] for review. [[AP Computer Science Principles]] requires students to complete the Create and Explore tasks, which are part of the AP grade for the class.\n[[File:AP Exams Taken in 2013.svg|300px|thumb|AP exams were taken by subject in 2013.]]\n\n==History==\nThe AP exams grew out of programs initiated in 1951. Part of the rationale for advanced placement given in 1952 was that \"advanced standing at the normal college-entering age after high school graduation is more desirable, for many reasons, than acceleration of able students out of high school at age 15\u00bd or 16...\".<ref>{{cite journal|first=Eric|last=Rothschild|journal=The History Teacher|title=Four Decades of the Advanced Placement Program|volume=32|issue=2|date=February 1999|pages=175\u2013206|doi=10.2307/494439|language=en|jstor=494439}}</ref> The first Advanced Placement exams were administered in 1954 by the [[Educational Testing Service]] (ETS) to students limited to 27 schools participating at that time. In 1955, the College Board assumed leadership of the program and testing, deciding on curricula and pedagogical approaches, while retaining ETS to design and score the tests. The exams were given nationally for the first time in May, 1956, and students could take whichever tests they wanted for a single $10 fee. The 2020 exams were taken as 45 minute online at home exams due to the 2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic\n\n==AP Exam Format==\nThe exams themselves do not grade the students' mastery of the course material in a traditional sense. Rather, the students themselves set the grading rubrics and the scale for the \"AP Grades\" of each exam.\n\nThe AP exams are graded each summer at a week-long \"grading camp.\" Both high school AP teachers and university professors are invited to grade the exams at a predetermined location. When the AP Reading is over for a particular exam, the free response scores are combined with the results of computer-scored multiple-choice questions based upon a previously announced weighting.\n\nThe Chief Reader (a college or university faculty member selected by the [[Educational Testing Service]] and [[The College Board]]) then meets with members of ETS and sets the cutoff scores for each AP Grade. The Chief Reader's decision is based upon what percentage of students earned each AP Grade over the previous three years, how students did on multiple-choice questions that are used on the test from year to year, how he or she viewed the overall quality of the answers to the free response questions, how university students who took the exam as PART A experimental studies did, and how students performed on different parts of the exam.\n\nNo one outside of ETS is allowed to find out a student's raw score on an AP Exam and the cutoff scores for a particular exam are only released to the public if that particular exam is released in total (this happens on a staggered schedule and occurs approximately once every five to seven years for each exam). Usually, a 70 to 75 percent out of 100 translates to a 5. However, there are some exams that are exceptions to this rule of thumb. The AP Grades that are reported to students, high schools, colleges, and universities in July are on AP's five-point scale:\n\n*'''5''': Extremely well qualified\n*'''4''': Very well qualified\n*'''3''': Qualified\n*'''2''': Possibly qualified\n*'''1''': No recommendation\n\n===Spring 2020 Exam Format Changes===\nOn March 20th, [[College Board]] announced<ref>https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/about-ap/news-changes/coronavirus-update</ref> changes to the spring 2020 exams due to the impact of [[COVID-19]] on school closings. The exams will be 45 minutes long with an online testing version for at-home exams. Any student already registered for an exam can choose to cancel at no charge. In the announcement, College Board also said that more information regarding the format of this year's AP exams will be announced by April 3rd.\n\nAdditionally, College Board will be providing a free distance learning curriculum<ref>https://apstudents.collegeboard.org/coronavirus-updates#free-ap-classes</ref> by [[livestreaming]] AP review lessons on [[YouTube]]. Not affiliated with College Board, the company Fiveable is also offering distance learning for AP students<ref>https://www.tun.com/blog/the-revised-ap-csp-exam-for-2020/</ref> for 15 AP subjects within English, STEM, history and social sciences.<ref>https://www.cnet.com/how-to/distance-learning-online-education-classes-for-every-age-and-grade/</ref>\n\n==University Credit==\n\n===In the United States and Elsewhere===\nSome<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marketplace.org/2013/02/20/education/more-colleges-stop-giving-credit-ap-exams|title=More colleges stop giving credit for AP exams|access-date=2017-05-24}}</ref> colleges and universities in the U.S. grant credits or advanced placement based on AP test scores; those in over twenty other countries do likewise. Policies vary by institution, but institutions that award credit usually<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apstudent.collegeboard.org/creditandplacement/credit-policy-detail?diCode=2116|title=AP Credit and Placement - AP Student - Search Credit Policy|website=apstudent.collegeboard.org|language=en|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref> require a score of 3 or higher on any given exam for credit to be granted or course prerequisites to be waived (and according to The College Board website, some will award an \"A\" grade for a 5 score{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}). Colleges may also take AP grades into account when deciding which students to accept, though this is not part of the official AP program.\n\nDespite some similarities to [[A Levels]] in that students choose to specialize in certain subjects, AP testing does not follow the national education curriculum of United Kingdom, not is it used as the exams for that curriculum. In that system, AS and A levels (or equivalents) are used in order to gain entry into universities, colleges and other higher education options. They are also often used in job applications. AP exam scores are widely recognized in the admissions process around the world, but credits are only sometimes accepted outside of Canada and the United States. As of August 2019, the College Board provided a downloadable [https://international.collegeboard.org/downloadable-resources list of universities] outside the US that recognize AP for admission and academic credit, in a file which they refer to as \"Global Higher Education Recognition.\" There were hundreds of universities in dozens of countries around the world that recognized AP exam scores in their admission process. AP credit is more limited, but not uncommon in countries that offer four-year undergraduate degrees and accept outside credit.\n\n== Calculator Policies<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://apcentral.collegeboard.com/apc/public/ap_coordinators/on_exam_day/232033.html#approved-calculators|title=AP Central - AP Calculator Policy|website=apcentral.collegeboard.com|language=en|access-date=2017-05-13}}</ref> ==\n[[File:AllowedCalculators.jpg|thumb|Allowed Calculators]]\nAs of 2017, AP students are allowed to use any of the approved calculators, including some [[Casio]], [[Texas Instruments]], and [[Hewlett-Packard]] calculators. Also, they may bring up to 2 calculators. Not all exams allow a calculator, but those that do allow all the allowed calculators to be used.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apstudent.collegeboard.org/takingtheexam/exam-policies/calculator-policy|title=AP Calculator Policy|website=apstudent.collegeboard.org|language=en|access-date=2017-05-24}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Glossary of biology]]\n*[[Glossary of chemistry terms|Glossary of chemistry]]\n*[[Glossary of economics]]\n*[[Glossary of physics]]\n*[[Glossary of probability and statistics]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Advanced Placement Exams}}\n[[Category:Advanced Placement| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Advanced Placement}}\n'''Advanced Placement examinations''' are [[exam]]s offered by the [[College Board]] and are taken each May by students.  The tests are the culmination of year-long [[Advanced Placement|Advanced Placement (AP)]] courses.  AP exams (with few exceptions<ref>[http://www.collegeboard.org CollegeBoard]</ref>) have a multiple-choice section and a free-response section.\n\n[[AP Studio Art]] requires students to submit a [[Career portfolio|portfolio]] for review. [[AP Computer Science Principles]] requires students to complete the Create and Explore tasks, which are part of the AP grade for the class.\n[[File:AP Exams Taken in 2013.svg|300px|thumb|AP exams were taken by subject in 2013.]]\n\n==History==\nThe AP exams grew out of programs initiated in 1951. Part of the rationale for advanced placement given in 1952 was that \"advanced standing at the normal college-entering age after high school graduation is more desirable, for many reasons, than acceleration of able students out of high school at age 15\u00bd or 16...\".<ref>{{cite journal|first=Eric|last=Rothschild|journal=The History Teacher|title=Four Decades of the Advanced Placement Program|volume=32|issue=2|date=February 1999|pages=175\u2013206|doi=10.2307/494439|language=en|jstor=494439}}</ref> The first Advanced Placement exams were administered in 1954 by the [[Educational Testing Service]] (ETS) to students limited to 27 schools participating at that time. In 1955, the College Board assumed leadership of the program and testing, deciding on curricula and pedagogical approaches, while retaining ETS to design and score the tests. The exams were given nationally for the first time in May, 1956, and students could take whichever tests they wanted for a single $10 fee. The 2020 exams were taken as 45 minute online at home exams due to the 2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic\n\n==AP Exam Format==\nThe exams themselves do not grade the students' mastery of the course material in a traditional sense. Rather, the students themselves set the grading rubrics and the scale for the \"AP Grades\" of each exam.\n\nThe AP exams are graded each summer at a week-long \"grading camp.\" Both high school AP teachers and university professors are invited to grade the exams at a predetermined location. When the AP Reading is over for a particular exam, the free response scores are combined with the results of computer-scored multiple-choice questions based upon a previously announced weighting.\n\nThe Chief Reader (a college or university faculty member selected by the [[Educational Testing Service]] and [[The College Board]]) then meets with members of ETS and sets the cutoff scores for each AP Grade. The Chief Reader's decision is based upon what percentage of students earned each AP Grade over the previous three years, how students did on multiple-choice questions that are used on the test from year to year, how he or she viewed the overall quality of the answers to the free response questions, how university students who took the exam as PART A experimental studies did, and how students performed on different parts of the exam.\n\nNo one outside of ETS is allowed to find out a student's raw score on an AP Exam and the cutoff scores for a particular exam are only released to the public if that particular exam is released in total (this happens on a staggered schedule and occurs approximately once every five to seven years for each exam). Usually, a 70 to 75 percent out of 100 translates to a 5. However, there are some exams that are exceptions to this rule of thumb. The AP Grades that are reported to students, high schools, colleges, and universities in July are on AP's five-point scale:\n\n*'''5''': Extremely well qualified\n*'''4''': Very well qualified\n*'''3''': Qualified\n*'''2''': Possibly qualified\n*'''1''': No recommendation\n\n===Spring 2020 Exam Format Changes===\nOn March 20th, [[College Board]] announced<ref>https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/about-ap/news-changes/coronavirus-update</ref> changes to the spring 2020 exams due to the impact of [[COVID-19]] on school closings. The exams will be 45 minutes long with an online testing version for at-home exams. Any student already registered for an exam can choose to cancel at no charge. In the announcement, College Board also said that more information regarding the format of this year's AP exams will be announced by April 3rd.\n\nAdditionally, College Board will be providing a free distance learning curriculum<ref>https://apstudents.collegeboard.org/coronavirus-updates#free-ap-classes</ref> by [[livestreaming]] AP review lessons on [[YouTube]]. Not affiliated with College Board, the company [[Fiveable]] is also offering distance learning for AP students<ref>https://www.tun.com/blog/the-revised-ap-csp-exam-for-2020/</ref> for 15 AP subjects within English, STEM, history and social sciences.<ref>https://www.cnet.com/how-to/distance-learning-online-education-classes-for-every-age-and-grade/</ref>\n\n==University Credit==\n\n===In the United States and Elsewhere===\nSome<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marketplace.org/2013/02/20/education/more-colleges-stop-giving-credit-ap-exams|title=More colleges stop giving credit for AP exams|access-date=2017-05-24}}</ref> colleges and universities in the U.S. grant credits or advanced placement based on AP test scores; those in over twenty other countries do likewise. Policies vary by institution, but institutions that award credit usually<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apstudent