g Kong.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/indians-including-iran-test-positive-for-coronavirus-abroad-confirms-mea-1656927-2020-03-18|title=276 Indians including 255 in Iran test positive for coronavirus abroad, confirms MEA|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> One Indian died in Iran on 20 March 2020.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Chaudhury|first=Dipanjan Roy|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-one-indian-in-iran-dead-government-gives-local-help-to-254-others/articleshow/74722021.cms|title=Covid-19: One Indian in Iran dead, Government gives local help to 254 others|date=20 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> A 3-year-old Indian girl tested positive in Singapore on 26 March, taking total to 277.<ref name=singapore>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/india/article/3-yr-old-indian-girl-among-73-new-coronavirus-cases-in-singapore-tally-of-infected-people-crosses/569723|title=3-yr-old Indian girl among 73 new coronavirus cases in Singapore, tally of infected people crosses 600|website=www.timesnownews.com|agency=PTI|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:90%;\"\n|+\nConfirmed cases of Indian nationals abroad\n!Country/Region\n!Active cases\n!Death\n!Total\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Hong Kong}}\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Iran}}\n|254\n|1<ref name=\":1\"/>\n|255\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Italy}}\n|5\n|0\n|5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Kuwait}}\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Rwanda}}\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|United Arab Emirates}}\n|12\n|0\n|12\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Sri Lanka}}\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Singapore}}\n|1\n|0\n|1<ref name=singapore/>\n|-\n!Total\n!276\n!1\n!277\n|}\n\n=== States and territories without confirmed cases ===\n\nNo confirmed cases have been reported in the following states and union territories\n\n* [[Arunachal Pradesh]]\n* [[Meghalaya]]\n* [[Nagaland]]\n* [[Sikkim]]\n* [[Tripura]]\n* [[Dadra and Nagar Haveli and Daman and Diu]]\n* [[Lakshadweep]]\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n**[[Indian local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic]]\n**[[Economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n**[[2020 India coronavirus lockdown]]\n*[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n**[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia]]\n***[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Asia]]\n***[[SAARC COVID-19 Emergency Fund]]\n*[[2020 stock market crash]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.mygov.in/covid-19 COVID-19] on [[MyGov.in]] \u2013 Government's portal for COVID-19\n* {{YouTube|playlist=PL1a9DHjZmejE-Ep2PAu2OR8HBfLP0BLIk|title=}} \u2013 COVID-19 Management videos by the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare]]\n*{{Cite book|last=Prasad|first=R.|url=https://creatives.thehindu.com/covid_19_ebook.pdf|title=The Pandemic Notebook|last2=Perappadan|first2=Bindu Shajan|last3=Shelar|first3=Jyoti|publisher=The Hindu|year=2020|isbn=|editor-last=George|editor-first=P.J.|location=|pages=|quote=A handy guide from The Hindu on understanding the coronavirus pandemic and staying protected against COVID-19}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n{{Portal bar|India|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India| ]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|India]]\n[[Category:2020 in India|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in India]]\n", "name_user": "KartikMistry", "label": "safe", "comment": "Ref convert.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_India"}
{"title_page": "Pig's blood cake", "text_new": "{{about|the street food|the solidified pig\u2019s blood|Pig blood curd}}\n[[File:\u5be7\u590f\u591c\u5e02_1.jpg|thumb|Pig's blood cake as sold in [[Taipei]]]]\n'''Pig's blood cake''' ({{zh|t={{linktext|\u8c6c\u8840\u7cd5}}|p=zh\u016b xi\u011b g\u0101o|poj=ti-hoeh-ko}} or {{zh|t={{linktext|\u8c6c\u8840\u7cbf}}|p=zh\u016b xi\u011b gu\u01d2|poj=ti-hoeh-ko\u00e9|labels=no}}) is a [[street food]] delicacy served on a stick from market stalls in [[Taiwan]]. It is made with [[pork]] blood, [[sticky rice]] and soy broth. It is either [[frying|fried]] or [[steaming|steamed]] and can be coated in peanut flour. Pig's blood cake came from Fujian to Taiwan and then developed.\n<ref>Kwang Ok Kim Re-orienting Cuisine: East Asian Foodways in the Twenty-First Century\uff0cBerghahn Books, 2015-2-1\uff0cp210</ref> It is eaten as a snack. It can also be cooked in a [[hot pot]]. It is served hot by street vendors who keep it warmed in a wooden box or metal steamer.<ref name=serious>{{cite web|last1=Chen|first1=Nicholas|title=Street Food in Taiwan: Pig's Blood Cake|url=http://www.seriouseats.com/2010/08/street-food-from-taiwan-pigs-blood-cake.html|website=Serious Eats: The Destination for Delicious |date=17 August 2010 |accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> A description from ''Seriouseats'' described it as cross between a [[rice cake]] and [[mochi]].<ref name=serious/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Taiwanese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Blood sausages]]\n[[Category:Pork dishes]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the street food|the solidified pig\u2019s blood|Pig blood curd}}\n[[File:\u5be7\u590f\u591c\u5e02_1.jpg|thumb|Pig's blood cake as sold in [[Taipei]]]]\n'''Pig's blood cake''' ({{zh|t={{linktext|\u8c6c\u8840\u7cd5}}|p=zh\u016b xi\u011b g\u0101o|poj=ti-hoeh-ko}} or {{zh|t={{linktext|\u8c6c\u8840\u7cbf}}|p=zh\u016b xi\u011b gu\u01d2|poj=ti-hoeh-ko\u00e9|labels=no}}) is a [[street food]] delicacy served on a stick from market stalls in [[Taiwan]]. It is made with [[pork]] blood, [[sticky rice]] and soy broth. It is either [[frying|fried]] or [[steaming|steamed]] and can be coated in peanut flour. Pig's blood cake came from Fujian to Taiwan and then developed \n<ref>Kwang Ok Kim Re-orienting Cuisine: East Asian Foodways in the Twenty-First Century\uff0cBerghahn Books, 2015-2-1\uff0cp210</ref>. It is eaten as a snack. It can also be cooked in a [[hot pot]]. It is served hot by street vendors who keep it warmed in a wooden box or metal steamer.<ref name=serious>{{cite web|last1=Chen|first1=Nicholas|title=Street Food in Taiwan: Pig's Blood Cake|url=http://www.seriouseats.com/2010/08/street-food-from-taiwan-pigs-blood-cake.html|website=Serious Eats: The Destination for Delicious |date=17 August 2010 |accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> A description from ''Seriouseats'' described it as cross between a [[rice cake]] and [[mochi]].<ref name=serious/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Taiwanese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Blood sausages]]\n[[Category:Pork dishes]]\n", "name_user": "Iseult", "label": "safe", "comment": "style", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pig%27s_blood_cake"}
